<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Germany Welcome EU Budget, Job Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- France and Germany, the primary
engines behind the European monetary union, welcomed an agreement
struck today by European Union (EU) finance ministers on a budget
pact and a jobs resolution on the sideline of an EU summit in
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
Chirac had welcomed the agreement which resulted from "a
perfect coordination between the president and the prime
minister," said Catherine Colonna, spokeswoman of Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was in line with the provisions of both French
President Jacques Chirac, a champion of domestic austerity
programs to qualify France for the single currency by its launch
date in 1999, and new socialist Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, who
calls for job creation and education reform, she said.
</P>
<P>
German Finance Minister Theo Waigal said that the deal was on
the right track and he was happy with the progress made. "We are
on a good path," he told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
The deal has reconciled Germany's insistence on strict monetary
discipline with France's demand for programs to stimulate growth
and jobs.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm told reporters that the
ministers had reached "complete agreement" on the stability pact,
which stricts budget rules for countries joining in EU's single
currency, and the resolution for growth and employment.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht treaty requires the EU members joining the
monetary union to reduce their public deficits to below 3 percent
of Gross Domestic Product and to keep a low unemployment rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
