<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt-For-Ivory Deal Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Rural communities from southern
Africa said today they are against the bid by some western
organisations to exchange debt owed by their countries for ivory.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conferfence of the ongoing 10th conference
of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species
(CITES) in Harare, the Southern African Forum for Communities and
Non-governmental Organisation (SAFCAN) said it wanted sustainable
trade and not aid.
</P>
<P>
SAFCAN representatives from seven southern African countries
said they supported the bid to downlist the elephant from
appendix one to appendix two because this would allow communities
to use the resources available to them.
</P>
<P>
The representatives said they would not support the
debt-for-ivory proposal because this would not directly benefit
conservation programmes in rural communities.
</P>
<P>
An international conservation group said at the beginning of
the conference last week that southern African countries could
consider selling their ivory stocks which have accumulated since
1989 to pay off their foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
"What we want is to manage our own resources and earn
something from those resources. We do not accept the
debt-for-ivory alternative," a Botswana representative said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
