<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldova Welcomes Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KISHINEV, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior Moldova official said
his country warmly welcomes foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Gheorghe Gaberi, Director of Foreign Investment Bureau,
Ministry of National Economy and Reform of Moldova, said in an
interview with Xinhua that as a bridge linking Europe with Asia,
Moldova is looking forward to more investments from the two
continents.
</P>
<P>
Moldovia has attracted 200 million dollars of foreign
investments, mainly from Russia, Germany and Luxemburg since its
independence nearly six years ago.
</P>
<P>
These investments are concentrated in the food processing
industry in the capital of Kishinev.
</P>
<P>
Moldova offers incentives to foreign investments, including
import duty exemption for machinery equipments, 50 percent profit
tax cut for the first five years, and free repatriation of
dividends.
</P>
<P>
Moldova has signed free trade agreements with neighboring
countries and the members of the Commonwealth of Independent
States.
</P>
<P>
Moldova, once an inland member republic of the former Soviet
Union, has an area of 33,700 square kilometers and a population of
4.5 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
