<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Youth Urged to Participate in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki today urged the youth of the country to be
more actively engaged in nation-building and creating a better
life for all.
</P>
<P>
He said that the youth could "play an indispensable role and
open the way for change" when making the call at a special youth
assembly in Cape Town to mark Youth Day and commemorate the 21th
anniversary of Soweto student uprising of June 16, 1976 to
protest the forced use of Afrikaans as a medium of instruction.
</P>
<P>
More than 140 young students were killed and 1000 injured when
police opened fire during the uprising.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said: "We can look forward to the future with optimism
and we await the birth of the national youth policy with great
expectations."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the country was moving in the right
direction and the government was prepared to invest in the youth,
urging the young people to join the fight against crime.
</P>
<P>
While referring to the issue of Afrikaans, Mbeki said the
government had taken a decision not to prohibit Afrikaans from
being used as a language of instruction at universities and other
tertiary institutions.
</P>
<P>
Afrikaners' fear that they and their language were being
marginalized was based on false information, said the Deputy
President, adding he was concerned about what appeared to be a
sense of unease about the future among the Afrikaner section of
the population, especially its youth.
</P>
<P>
Afrikaner youth representatives speaking during the assembly
proceedings also urged the government not to repeat the mistakes
of the past by conducting a policy of language imperialism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the chairwoman of the National Youth Movement
Mahlengi Bhengu told the assembly that June 16 should be observed
in a responsible manner.
</P>
<P>
"Use the opportunity to tell the government about the problems
you face where you live," said Bhengu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
