<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls for Iranian Co-op on Border Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today urged Iran to make
further efforts to ensure the security along the Turkish-Iranian
border areas.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry Deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli told
a weekly press briefing that more work had to be done to make the
border of the two countries a peaceful region.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that there have already existed some mechanisms
designed to ensure border tranquility, Atacanli said Turkey was
not satisfied with the present situation.
</P>
<P>
"No concrete results have been achieved so far in this
respect," the spokesman said, adding that Turkey was monitoring
closely the developments on the Turkish-Iranian border.
</P>
<P>
He said that it would be possible for military officials to
participate in certain security committees between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Ankara has conveyed its security concern to Iran time and
again, and hoped to see a positive reaction, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani has denied that Iran is
hosting the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) rebels, outlawed in
Turkey for fighting a separatist war for autonomy in eastern and
southeastern Turkey since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly accused Iran of supporting the PKK
rebels, who it alleged were holing up in Iran to launch sporadic
attacks and cause disturbances along the Iranian-Turkish border.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, who is in here to attend a summit of eight Muslim
states, told reporters that the infiltration of the PKK rebels
into Iran also affects the benefits of the Iranian people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
