<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho PM Explains His Political Moves to State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho Prime Minister Ntsu
Mokhehle today has given a detailed explanation of his latest
political moves to the Lesotho Council of State, reported the
South African Press Association from Maseru, capital of the
land-locked kingdom.
</P>
<P>
An informed government source was quoted as saying that the
meeting, called by King Letsie III and attended by several other
members of the Council, asked many questions relating to
Mokhehle's latest political moves, which allegedly plunged
Lesotho into a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Mokhehle resigned as leader of the ruling
Basutoland Congress Party (BCP) and formed a new political party,
the Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD), to which he transferred
governance immediately followed its registration.
</P>
<P>
During Monday's hearing, the Council members asked whether
Mokhehle's political movements did not imply that his government
should have resigned and sought a new mandate under a new
political party, said the source.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehel's reply was not because "there is a separation
between political party affairs and the government".
</P>
<P>
Following Mokhehle's explanation, senior government officials
were convinced that Mokhehle's moves constituted no violation of
the kingdom's supreme law, the constitution.
</P>
<P>
However, during a mass protest march in Maseru, the BCP
presented a petition to head of state King Letsie III, demanding
the resignation of Mokhehle.
</P>
<P>
The petition requested the King to ensure that democratic rule
was reinstated in Lesotho, failing which the people would have no
option but to see to it that this was done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
