<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-16 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Blames Arafat for Renewed Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu today charged Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat for
giving order to the recent rioting renewed by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and
Defense Committee, Netanyahu held Arafat responsible for the
Palestinian rioting last Thursday near the Kush Katif settlement
in Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
One Palestinian died and several others were wounded in clashes
with Israeli soldiers who fired rubber bullets and tear gas to
disperse the protesters.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu noted that Arafat was careful not to launch a new
round of full-out violence for two reasons: tougher reaction from
Israel and international criticism.
</P>
<P>
He said Arafat's game of playing with pressures on Israel from
Egypt and the United States had failed. On the contrary, the
U.S. was exerting pressure on Arafat for the alleged official
corruption and the murder of Palestinian land dealers who sold
land to Jews.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu claimed that the Palestinian National Authority was
at a political crossroads now: either to advance peace or return
to violence. He expressed hope that the Palestinian side would
stop the violence and resume negotiations with Israel in order to
continue the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the situation between Israel and Syria and
Lebanon, Netanyahu said he saw no immediate signs of impending
war with Syria. But He quickly added it did not mean that Israel
does not maintain vigilance.
</P>
<P>
On the continued clashes in south Lebanon, Netanyahu said
Israel did not intend to occupy Lebanon, and its occupation of the
so-called south Lebanon security zone was only aimed at preventing
Hezbollah forces from attacking its northern border.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu came under strong criticism in the committee from
opposition lawmakers, including Labor Party's faction chairman
Rannan Cohen and Meretz leader Yossi Sarid. Both of them accused
Netanyahu of leading the country to new clashes with the
Palestinians, and possibly with the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
Labor's new leader Ehud Barak also pointed an accusing finger
at Netanyahu for his hardline policies which he said not only
lead the country to the brink of war, but also push it onwards.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Israel had nothing to gain from the
confrontation -- although Israel could inflict 10 times more
casualties in clashes with its enemies, but it would also pay a
high price.
</P>
<P>
Barak advised Netanyahu be ready to make compromises by
taking into account of the vital interests of the Palestinian
side, while trying to preserve Israel's own security
interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
