<HEADLINE> Indonesia Vows to Implement Rights in Own Norms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto said
his country will implement human rights principles and
democratization according to its own norms.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters this morning aboard the plane taking him
home from Istanbul, Turkey, the president said pressure on
Indonesia to democratize and implement human rights principles is
getting stronger, the official Antara News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was referring to U.S. Senator Patrick Kennedy who has
recently criticized Indonesia's human rights record at the U.S.
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Kennedy's stance and the U.S. Congress' plan to issue an
anti-Indonesia bill has pushed Indonesia to cancel the planned
purchase of nine F-16 fighters from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto attended the Development 8 (D-8) summit in Istanbul on
June 15.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 groups Bangladesh, Egypt, Indonesia, Iran, Malaysia,
Nigeria, Pakistan and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
On the D-8, the president said the group was formed to make its
member countries' cooperation with bigger groups more effective
and efficient.
</P>
<P>
At its summit on Sunday, the D-8 agreed to promote dialogue
instead of confrontation, cooperation instead of exploitation,
justice instead of double standard, equality instead of
discrimination and respect instead of oppression.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh will host the second D-8 summit next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
