<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Population Meeting Opens in Addis Ababa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A 4-day second general
assembly of the African Population Commission opened here today,
to discuss how to meet the population challenges facing the poor
continent.
</P>
<P>
In his statement at the opening ceremony, Vijay S. Makhan,
assistant secretary general of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU), said African continent is the last region to venture into
the field of elaborating population policies aimed at addressing
conclusively the challenges of the time.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that with an annual population growth of almost
three percent, the African continent's population is expected to
reach 850 million by the end of the century and by the year 2025,
the figure will be doubled to 1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
The OAU official wondered in his statement how African
countries can produce enough food, create enough jobs and provide
adequate education for an additional 15-20 million people each
year when they are unable to do so for their present population.
</P>
<P>
He urged African countries to "adopt bold measures and take
courageous steps to prevent the continent from further stagnation
on account of its hitherto inability to tackle the population
problems".
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Ethiopian Minister of Economic
Development and Cooperation Girma Biru emphasized that the
challenge facing Africa today remains great and the imbalance
between excessively rapid population growth and social and
economic development still continues.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the assembly has a vital role to play in helping
OAU member countries to review the issues and challenges in
Africa, devise policies, strategies and programs to address these
challenges, he added.
</P>
<P>
The population meeting, jointly organized by the OAU, UN
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and the African Development
Bank, is to review population and development activities, share
experiences and revise strategies to accelerate the
implementation of the Dakar/Ngor declaration and the pledges made
in Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
