<HEADLINE> Pakistan's PM in Iran for Talks on Afghan Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif arrived here today for talks with Iranian leaders on the
Afghan issue and bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Sharif was received at the airport by Iranian Foreign Minister
Ali Akbar Velayati. He said upon his arrival that Pakistan
believes that the Afghan issue should be solved by peaceful
instead of military means.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani is now holding talks
with Sharif in Sadabad Palace in northern Tehran, the capital of
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is expected to hold talks with Iranian President-elect
Mohammad Khatami Tuesday on the bilateral issues and international
topics of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Khatami today called for broadening relations between Iran and
Pakistan. He has sent separate cables to Pakistan President
Farooq Ahmad Khan Leghari and Sharif, urging Pakistan to
consolidate the friendship between the two neighboring Muslim
countries.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is widely believed to have given financial and
military support to the Taliban Islamic militia, a faction that
captured the Afghan capital of Kabul in September and took control
of two-thirds of the country.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was also the first country to recognize the Taliban
government.
</P>
<P>
Taliban repeatedly accused Iran of supporting the ousted
government of Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Iran has denied giving military assistance to any of the
Afghan factions, saying it had sent only humanitarian aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
