<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Clash with Israeli Soldiers in Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- At least 10 Palestinian
protesters and one Israeli soldier were injured during the clashes
between them for the third consecutive day today in the West Bank
town of Hebron, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The clashes took place along the line between Jewish
neighborhoods and Palestinian areas in the disputed city.
</P>
<P>
It was the third straight day when violent confrontations
erupted in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, apparently triggered
off by the United States Congress resolution last week to
recognize united Jerusalem as Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
In the Gaza Strip, Jewish settlers of Morag Settlement
opened fire at a group Palestinians, claiming that the
Palestinians "have broke into the settlement property and tried
to move a fence."
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, the US House of Representatives voted 406-17
to recognize Jerusalem as the undivided capital of Israel,
despite opposition by the US government.
</P>
<P>
The house also voted to provide 100 million US dollars
for moving the US Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, who see East Jerusalem as the capital of
a future Palestinian State, sharply criticized the resolution,
which they said would hurt the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) cabinet
issued a statement, blaming the US, the Israeli soldiers, and
Jewish settlers for what it said was an "explosive situation
everywhere because of Israeli settlement aggression."
</P>
<P>
PNA chief Jerusalem representative Faisal Husseini, who
participated in a demonstration today opposite the US Consulate
in East Jerusalem, warned that if the US approves the
resolution, "the whole peace process will be lost."
</P>
<P>
The US congressional resolution about Jerusalem was taken by
Palestinians as implicit US support for Israel's stand for
creating facts on the ground prior to final status
negotiations which include Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak also criticized the
resolution, saying "the resolution was unwise, especially that
it came at a time when the peace process was passing
through a crisis, which would escalate the situation."
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians have been
stalled since March when Israel started to build a
controversial new Jewish neighborhood at Har Homa (Jabal Abu
Ghneim) on the southeastern outskirts of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians have said that Israel must stop the construction
before talks can resume, while, Israel is insisting that the
PNA must crack down on terror and reestablish full security
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
