<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Urges Prompt Lift of Ban On Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African Unity
(OAU) today called for a prompt lift of international sanctions
against Libya over the Lockerbie crisis and aired support for
Tripoli's overtures to settle the dispute with the West.
</P>
<P>
Salim Ahmed Salim, OAU secretary general, who arrived here last
Friday for a week-long visit, made the statement today after
meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on several
issues on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
The OAU secretary general said that he probed with Moussa the
UN imposed sanctions and flight embargo on Libya and the Tripoli's
dispute with the West.
</P>
<P>
The UN imposed sanctions against Tripoli for its refusal to
hand over two Libyans suspected of involvement in the bombing of a
Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988, killing 270
people on board.
</P>
<P>
Libyan leader Mummar Gaddafi has suggested the two stand trial
anywhere other than in the U.S. and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Salim called for the removal of such sanctions that are "not in
the interest of the Libyan people and the African region."
</P>
<P>
"The OAU called for an immediate end of the sanctions imposed
on Libya and urged the implementation of the initiatives and
proposals made by the OAU, Arab League and Non-Aligned Movement to
secure a solution to the crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
The OAU sees that these proposals "the only way out of the
current crisis and ending the sufferings of region, Libya and the
entire African continent, he added.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief said that he will discuss with Arab League
Secretary General Esmat Abdel Meguid on coordinating stances of
the League and his organization.
</P>
<P>
The Libya-West crisis was discussed for the first time at the
latest African summit which called for lifting the sanctions and
taking temporary measures to help ease the sufferings of the
Libyan people.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, during his two-day visit to
the Libyan coastal city of Tobruk on June 12-13, also denounced
the UN imposed ban on Libya and urged its immediate removal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
