<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lesotho Government Faces Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhao Yi)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 16 (xinhua) -- The Lesotho cabinet led by
Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle has been strongly denounced as the
"usurped" government by the former ruling Basutoland Congress
Party (BCP) and its supporters since he formed the Lesotho
Congress for Democracy (LCD) last week.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle announced on June 9 the formation of LCD and
immediately transferred the government power to the newly formed
party, saying that his new party had controlled a majority
parliament with the support of 41 of 64 parliament members.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle's moves sent shockwaves in the tiny land-locked
mountain kingdom, forcing opposition parties to form a coalition
with the BCP, which unanimously condemned the move and termed it
"unconstitutional" or even as "coup d'etat".
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, 20 parliament members of BCP walked out the
National Assembly in protest against Mokhehle's latest political
moves.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the walkout, some BCP members questioned Parliament
Speaker Teboho Kolane why he was legitimizing the "unlawful"
actions taken by Mokhehle. There were several attacks by members
of the BCP against the speaker, accusing him of bias, informed
sources said.
</P>
<P>
They were demanding a normal swearing-in process for members
of the new party, including the prime minister, as well as
notification of the changes to the King Letsie III.
</P>
<P>
Several thousand supporters of Lesotho political parties,
waving the multiple colors of party flags, today participated in
a demonstration against the Mokhehle government, informed sources
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
"The march against the usurped government of Mokhehle was very
successful. People came in from all districts in trucks and
minibuses to support our protest against Mokhehle," demonstration
organizer Vincent Malebo said.
</P>
<P>
A BCP memorandum was handed to King Letsie III's secretary
Mabotse Lerothodi during the demonstration, Malebo said, adding
that the King was at that time attending a council of state
meeting, where Mokhehle was explaining his latest political
moves.
</P>
<P>
In the memorandum, the BCP pointed out that the formation of
Mokhehle's LCD in the National Assembly was not only a
manipulation of the democratic process and a travesty of justice,
but also a betrayal of the trust that was reposed upon him as
leader of the BCP, Malebo said.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, singed by its Secretary-General Godfrey
Kolisang, also drew the attention of the King to Mokhehle's
resignation from BCP, both as leader and member -- a move which,
the BCP said, carried serious implications for the people of
Lesotho as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"Mokhehle's resignation signifies a complete failure on his
party as leader to meet and satisfy the aspirations of the party
members and the electorate," Malebo quoted the memorandum as
saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Mokhehle said he left the BCP due to infighting which
plagued the party for a long time, noting that his opponents
within the party made it difficult for him to run the party
effectively.
</P>
<P>
For now, there is no sign of any suspension of anti-government
campaign in Lesotho. The opposition coalition has vowed to make
the country ungovernable and parliament unworkable, yet
Mokhehle's loyalists, ignoring the threats, said the prime
minister would continue his leadership as he enjoyed support of
the majority in parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
