<HEADLINE> GCC Officials Discuss Integrated Power Grid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Electricity
Under-secretaries of the six Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states
today started a two-day meeting in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia to discuss
a possible unified grid, reports reaching here from Jeddah said.
</P>
<P>
An initial feasibility study envisaged the project to be in
two phases with the first aiming at linking Kuwait, Saudi Arabia,
Bahrain and Qatar while the second phase linking the United Arab
Emirates and Oman, according to Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency said quoting official sources that the total cost
of the project is assessed to be at 2.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is being held after the GCC finance and economy
ministers agreed to allow private sector to invest in the proposed
project, sources said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will touch on fees to be charged by member states,
minimum costs to be encumbered and other operational aspects.
</P>
<P>
No timetable has been set up for the completion of the
project which is expected to make more convenient and efficient
use of the power source in the GCC member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
