<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Rejects US Congress Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia today rejected
the U.S. congress recognition of Jerusalem as the "undivided
capital" of Israel and the decision to allocate 100 million
U.S. dollars to move its embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Information Minister Fuad Faresi said in a statement
after a weekly cabinet meeting chaired by Saudi King Fahd Ibn
Abdul-Aziz that the resolution adopted by the American House of
Representatives on Jerusalem would undermine the international
efforts to save the deadlocked Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, Faresi said that the
cabinet expressed appreciation over the position of U.S.
President Bill Clinton's administration which criticized the
Congress resolution.
</P>
<P>
Saudi second Deputy Prime Minister and Defense Minister Prince
Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz said after his talks with U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen in Jeddah last Saturday that Riyadh fully
rejected the decision to move the U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem,
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan said "Saudi Arabia will be glad to hear the
U.S. leaders' opposition to this decision."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress passed the resolution last Tuesday amid
international criticism and Arab attacks against Israeli
insistence on the construction of a new Jewish settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs considered the decision as an encouragement to
Israel's continued expansionist policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
