<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Adopt EMU, Jobs Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union leaders
adopted at their summit meeting in Amsterdam today two resolutions
designed to strict budget rules in the monetary union while
putting strong emphasis on fighting unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok, who hosts the two-day EU summit
in Amsterdam, announced the adoption "with great satisfaction" at
a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The European Council Resolution on Growth and Employment said
that employment issues would be kept "firmly at the top of the
political agenda of the Union."
</P>
<P>
The employment accord, a non-binding political resolution that
includes a role for the European Investment Bank, comes in
response to the new French government's demands that more should
be done to help the 18 million unemployed in the Union.
</P>
<P>
However, German Finance Minister Theo Waigel said that the
employment resolution involved no additional spending for
job-creation projects.
</P>
<P>
France wants funding for major infrastructure programs such as
Trans-European Networks (TENs) as a way for creating jobs. TENs
include large road, rail and telecommunications links between and
within the 15 EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
But Germany has ruled out costly Europe-wide job-creation
programs, which, it argues, have in the past merely raised
inflation and interest rates and failed to cut unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Bonn believes that the way to fight joblessness is through
structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
The stability pact, an accord reached in principle in December
to stop countries running large deficits after the single currency
is launch in January 1999, was, as expected, adopted unchanged
from its original form, despite French protests in advance of the
meeting that they may need more time to consider the pact before
agreeing it.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch prime minister also confirmed at the press conference
that a special EU summit meeting would be held during the
six-month Luxembourg EU presidency, which starts on July 1, to
address the 15-nation bloc's high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"The summit will not create miracles, but we can learn from
others' experiences (in fighting unemployment)," the Dutch prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the two resolutions has reconciled Germany's
insistence on strict monetary discipline with French demands for
programs to stimulate growth and jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar to Introduce Value Added Tax System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government has
accepted and confirmed its readiness to introduce the Value Added
Tax (VAT) system following recent consultations between the Isles
government and the Union government of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania Revenue Authority (TRA), Commissioner General,
Melkizedeck E. Sanare said here today that his authority was
assisting in the introduction of VAT in Zanzibar and details are
being worked out with the Ministry of Finance in Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
"The VAT Bill gazetted in March 1997 was for a Mainland VAT
system only. Following recent consultations between the Union
government and the government of Zanzibar the latter has
confirmed its readiness to introduce a VAT system," said Sanare
in a press statement.
</P>
<P>
The TRA chief said that the Vat Implementation Project to be
introduced in the country next year, was currently being funded
by the World Bank, European Union (EU) and the Union government.
</P>
<P>
Sanare said the World Bank has provided a loan of 1.1 million
US Dollars for professional staff, technical assistance, office
equipment and training since 1995.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU has provided a grant of 1.52 US Dollars which
covers computerisation, technical assistance and staff training
and the government of Tanzania has submitted a request to the EU
for additional funding for the program.
</P>
<P>
"The government has been providing funds for meeting the
recurrent expenses of the project," said Sanare, adding that in
the next financial year the government was also intending to fund
the project through its allocation to TRA.
</P>
<P>
He said introduction of VAT in the country was a decision of
the government aimed primarily at broadening the tax base and
increasing government revenue.
</P>
<P>
The authority last month also said that advantages of VAT
would be abollition of a number of taxes sucha as sales tax,
hotel levy and stamp duty.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the introduced VAT system was not
prohibitive and unfriendly to the tax-payer and was also self
policing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
