<HEADLINE> Pan-African News Agency to Go Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) said today that African ministers of information will
discuss a plan to privatize their regional news network.
</P>
<P>
This came in a report prepared by OAU Secretary General Salim
Ahmed Salim on information and communication in Africa, endorsed
at a working session of the Inter-Governmental Council on
Information and Communication today.
</P>
<P>
The report stated that a plan has been approved to revive the
financially-strapped Pan-African News Agency (PANA) in cooperation
with the UNESCO and the OAU.
</P>
<P>
PANA Board of Directors has proposed selling 25 percent of its
capital to national news agencies in African countries and offer
the rest for private interests.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif said earlier
today that the ownership and service of a restructured PANA has
to remain African in order to maintain its function as Africa's
voice to the world and information disseminator.
</P>
<P>
Discussions around PANA will be high on the agenda of the
three-day meeting in Cairo of the information ministers from more
than 30 African countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ministers will discuss a proposal to establish
an OAU radio station to enable Africans to participate in issues
related to their continent.
</P>
<P>
They will also review offers submitted by many international
institutions to launch the African Satellite and an African
information system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
