<HEADLINE> PKK Killed 8 Soldiers in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The rebels of the illegal Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) today killed eight soldiers of government
troops in two attacks in southeastern Turkey, the state-run Radio
TRT reported this evening.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the PKK militants launched rockets at a
military vehicle at about 07:00 a.m. local time (04:00 GMT),
killing six military personnel including one officer in Hakkari
province bordering Iran and northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported that a group
of the PKK rebels today attacked a train on the Elazig-Tatvan
railway with rockets near Suveren Station of Genc town of Bingol
province.
</P>
<P>
Two soldiers were killed and four others wounded in the
attack, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the agency said that the village guards shot dead
10 PKK guerrillas Sunday night in the armed clashes in Kizilsu
city of Sirnak province in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Three village guards were sent to a hospital for treatment
after being wounded in the clashes, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels launched attacks against military and civilian
targets in southeastern Turkey while about 50,000-strong Turkish
government troops have carried out a massive cross-border
military operations against PKK bases in northern Iraq since May
14.
</P>
<P>
More than 23,000 people, including PKK rebels, civilians and
government troops, have been killed in conflicts since August
1984 when the PKK started a separatist war for autonomy in
eastern and southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
