<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Adopt EMU, Jobs Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union leaders
adopted today the jobs agreement reached by their finance
ministers earlier to incorporate an employment resolution in the
stability pact.
</P>
<P>
It was announced by Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok, who hosts the
two-day EU summit in Amsterdam, "with great satisfaction" at a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
Kok also confirmed that a special EU summit meeting would be
held during the six-month Luxembourg EU presidency, which starts
on July 1, to address the 15-nation bloc's high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"The summit will not create miracles, but we can learn from
others' experiences (in fighting unemployment)," the Dutch prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The jobs deal has reconciled Germany's insistence on strict
monetary discipline with French demands for programs to stimulate
growth and jobs.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm told reporters that the
ministers had reached "complete agreement" on the stability pact,
which stricts budget rules for countries joining in the EU's
single currency, and the resolution for growth and employment.
</P>
<P>
EU monetary affairs commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy told
reporters after the finance ministers' meeting that there would be
a link between an EU budget pact and the one on growth and
employment.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the accord provided for a special lending
program by the European Investment Bank, the EU's main lending
arm, to help small businesses and high-technology companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
