<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Province to Sue Tobacco Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- In a ground-breaking move in
Canada, British Columbia (B.C.) province will introduce
legislation today that will enable the province and its residents
to team up in class-action suit against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
It is the province's hope that the law would help claw back
some of the estimated 370 million U.S. dollars it pays each year
to treat smoking-related diseases, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
The threat of broad, government-backed class-suits is designed
to persuade the tobacco companies that it is time to become "more
responsible corporate citizens," said a B.C. government official.
</P>
<P>
"We are asking them to change their ways. If they don't, we are
saying we'll change for them," the official was quoted as saying
by the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The proposed law would speed up litigation by making it easier
to prove smoking's harmful effects, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time in B.C. and Canada as a whole that
the cost of smoking-related health costs is recovered directly
from the tobacco industry, not via the tax system.
</P>
<P>
The B.C. government will also propose hefty fees for tobacco
manufacturers if they wish to sell cigarettes in the province,
seek a crackdown on teen-age smoking.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that some 5,500 B.C. residents are killed by
smoking each year, more than drug overdoses, alcohol, car
accidents, suicides and AIDS combined together.
</P>
<P>
Today's move by B.C. is being closely watched by the federal
government and the other provinces, which are considering similar
court efforts to recoup billions of dollars that smoking costs
them each year.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco companies in the United States have begun to buckle
under the threat of class-action lawsuits from at least 37 states
in recent weeks, which would be boost for their Canadian
counterparts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
