<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Women Executives Increases Sharply in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- More women are reaching the top of
the business ladder and the pay gap with their male counterparts
is narrowing, the Institutes of Management said today.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, the number of female executives has
risen 60 percent, accounting for 15.2 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The surge in women's presence in management, including in the
boardroom, comes as some companies are appointing high-profile
women to senior posts, such as Marjorie Scardino, chief executive
of Pearson.
</P>
<P>
Personnel and marketing are the most promising routes for women
to get to the top. There are as many female personnel managers as
there are men, while one in three marketing managers is a woman.
</P>
<P>
The findings emerge from the institute's national management
salary survey, which covers 867 directors and more than 23,600
managers in almost 500 companies.
</P>
<P>
Women had bigger pay rises than men last year. Their salaries
rose 7.4 percent compared with 4.7 percent in the previous year,
while rises for men were up from 4.7 percent to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The typical female manager is 37, earns 31,550 pounds (50,480
US dollars) a year and has been with her present employer for 11
years.
</P>
<P>
Their male counterpart is 44, earns 35,761 pounds (57.218
dollars) and has spent the last 17 years with his company.
</P>
<P>
At boardroom level, the average female director is 40, earns
71,126 pounds (113,802 dollars) and has worked in her present firm
for eight years.
</P>
<P>
Their typical male colleague is 48, earns 91,957 pounds
(147,131 dollars) and has 14 years with his current employer.
</P>
<P>
Another survey of 4 million executives, compiled by a business
information agency, also showed that 29 percent of British company
directors are female. And it revealed that they are generally
younger than male directors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Calls for Poverty Eradication in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) today called for the freeing of African
countries from the devastating burden of debt and the adoption of
other actions to eradicate poverty in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Marking today's observance of the Day of the African Child,
Carol Bellamy, UNICEF executive director, said that huge debt
obligations in many African countries were severely undermining
their capacity to care for their children. Total external debt in
sub-Saharan Africa represented about 800 dollars per child.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that there was no "magic formula" for sustainable
economic growth and the eradication of poverty in Africa, she
called for action on a number of fronts -- the facilitation of
broad-based economic growth, the provision of basic social
services for all, the enhancement of income opportunities for the
poor, a fair international trading system, foreign investment and
donor assistance.
</P>
<P>
The answer was to couple appropriate economic policies with
sustainable investment in children and their families, she
stressed.
</P>
<P>
She also noted that recent reports of the United Nations
Development Program pointed to the potential for real economic
recovery in Africa. In 1995, economic growth in Africa rose above
population growth for the first time in a decade. In 1986, 18
countries recorded more than 5 percent growth in their gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
"There is truly good news in these figures for a continent too
often associated with want and suffering," she said.
</P>
<P>
Despite these positive trends, Bellamy acknowledged that the
progress was fragile. In sub-Saharan Africa, some 40 percent of
the population -- more than 220 million people -- still lived
below the poverty line. As large families were most vulnerable to
poverty, children were the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
"It's an outrage that in this era of unprecedented global
wealth creation, about one quarter of the world's population lives
in poverty," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
