<HEADLINE> British PM Condemns Killing of N.Irish Police by IRA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
today condemned the IRA for the killing of two policemen in
Northern Ireland and decided to cut off official contacts with
the IRA's political wing Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
Blair, while attending an EU summit meeting in Amsterdam, said
in a statement that the IRA's "cynicism and hypocrisy are
sickening. Their actions defy normal understanding. It is
difficult to interpret this latest attack as anything but a signal
that Sinn Fein and the IRA are not interested in peace and
democracy."
</P>
<P>
He said any further meeting with Sinn Fein was now out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
"My reaction to this outrage is the reaction of decent people
everywhere -- one of horror at the act of murder and anger at what
looks like a deliberate attempt to place obstacles in the road of
peace," local reports quoted the prime minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Two policemen were killed at close range by gunmen late this
morning in the town of Lurgan, southwest of Belfast, and the IRA
claimed responsibility hours later for the murder.
</P>
<P>
Both Britain's Labor government and Dublin resumed talks with
Sinn Fein last month with the hope of bringing about a new IRA
cease-fire and reaching an agreement to end Northern Ireland's 28
years of conflict.
</P>
<P>
In response to today's attack, a spokesman for the Northern
Ireland office announced that the government had broken off
contacts with Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
"Following today's murders there is no question of agreeing to
meet Sinn Fein," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
