<HEADLINE> Cameroun's New Parliament to Convene First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The first ordinary session of
Cameroun's national assembly for 1997-1998 legislative year will
be held in Yaounde tomorrow, local radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Cameroun's prime minister Peter Mafany Musonge is expected to
present the government's social economic policies at the session.
</P>
<P>
The session coming two weeks after the Cameroun supreme court
declared the last May 17 legislative election results will
validate the candidature of parliamentarians and examine the
state budget.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected that this session will put in place newly
created but yet to function institutions provided for by the new
constitution of January 18, 1996 such as constitutional council.
</P>
<P>
Seven political parties are going to sit in this assembly
including the Social Democratic Front (SDF), the major opposition
party in the country who boycotted the 1992 legislative
discussion. John Fru Ndi, the national chairman of the SDF told
reporters in a press conference held in Yaounde today that the
SDF will participate in the first ordinary session of the
national assembly. 
</P>
