<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Housing Starts Down for Third Straight Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Housing starts in the U.S.
dropped by 4.8 percent in May, the third straight month of
decline, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that construction of new homes and
apartments totaled 1.40 million at a seasonally adjusted annual
rate, down from 1.47 million in April.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time since January-March of 1995 that the
starts have fallen for three consecutive months.
</P>
<P>
For the year so far, the housing starts in the U.S. were 3.3
percent fewer than the first five months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report said that single-family starts, about 80 percent of
new construction, were down 2.5 percent, the third straight
decline.
</P>
<P>
Construction of apartments and condominiums fell 12.2 percent
after advancing 4.5 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, housing starts in the West rose by 5.2 percent and
were flat in the Midwest. They fell by 11.3 percent in the South
and 8.1 percent in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
Applications for building permits, often a barometer of future
activity, inched up 0.1 percent in May after falling 1 percent a
month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Recent signs showed that the U.S. housing market will remain
strong in the second half of the year because of favorable weather
and lower borrowing costs. The U.S. Federal Home Loan Mortgage
Corp. said that 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages averaged 7.93
percent in May, compared with the high rate of 8.32 percent last
June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
