<HEADLINE> Algeria's Shore Exposed to Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Algeria's shore is facing a threat
of pollution as oil leaked in the port city of Sakikda, some 500
kilometers east of the capital city of Algiers, approaches.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources disclosed today that the leakage took
place Sunday with 200 cubic meters of crude oil flowing into the
sea, because the oil pipe in the harbor were worn out.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses indicated that large quantities of fish and other
marine lives were seen floating along the shore.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the pipe was soon fixed after the accident
happened and the petroleum in the pipe, estimated at 500 cubic
meters, was discharged. The petroleum was carried away by 18 oil
tanker-trucks.
</P>
<P>
A similar accident occurred last December when an unspecified
quantity of a poisonous chemical was leaked, the sources said,
without giving details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
