<HEADLINE> Russia-DPRK Consultations End in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) today ended their consultations on
the development of bilateral relations, which started Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass news agency, the consultations
further coordinated a draft interstate treaty to replace the
former treaty signed by leaders of the Soviet Union and the DPRK
in 1961.
</P>
<P>
The two-day consultations focused on five major projects, that
is, cooperation in oil refining, the use of the Rajin port by
Russian vessels, joint investments in the Rajin-Sonbong free
economic zone, development of a coke field in Yakutia, and
cooperation at a metallurgical plant built with participation of
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that another round of negotiations to
coordinate the draft text is still needed and is expected to take
place in the second half of this year in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to hold the second meeting of the
bilateral intergovernmental commission on trade, economic,
scientific and technical cooperation in Moscow in fall.
</P>
<P>
Visiting here, Lee In Koo, deputy foreign minister of the DPRK,
met with Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov Monday and
passed over to the Russian minister a message from DPRK
Vice-Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Kim Yong Nam. Lee In Koo
also invited Primakov to visit Pyongyang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
