<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rita Fan Shrugs Off Boycott of Swearing-in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Rita Fan, president of the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, today shrugged off some western countries'
threat to boycott the swearing-in of the interim legislature.
</P>
<P>
"They have the right not to be there. The PLC works for the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), and doesn't work
for the government of any foreign country," said Rita Fan at the
fourth of a series of news conferences organized by the Foreign
Correspondents' Club for journalists who have come to the city for
coverage of the handover.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair said that they would not attend the
swearing-in ceremony of the PLC on July 1.
</P>
<P>
"I wouldn't even try to imagine or interpret the action," said
the PLC president. She said there are various political
considerations behind the boycott threat.
</P>
<P>
"Does it really matter to me that other people thousands of
miles away have misunderstanding of what we're doing here? It
really doesn't matter," she said.
</P>
<P>
The PLC president explained why the interim legislature came
into being. "Establishment of the PLC is not the best option, but
it is the best option in a situation that was not created by us."
</P>
<P>
Since the current Legislative Council produced under Chris
Patten's political reform package in violation of the Sino-British
Joint Declaration has to stop functioning by June 30, 1997, it is
necessary to set up a law-making body to avoid a legal vacuum
right after the establishment of the HKSAR. As an interim
arrangement, the PLC only enacts laws that are absolutely
indispensable to the HKSAR and will not extend beyond June 30,
1998, she said.
</P>
<P>
In response to media misunderstanding of the PLC, she said:
"The best way to judge a person, an organization, a government or
a country is to judge them after the event."
</P>
<P>
So far the PLC has passed three readings on nine bills and
endorsed three motions. "These bills have no legal effect until
July 1," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
On the coming Saturday, the PLC will hold its last meeting in
Shenzhen, south China, before Hong Kong's handover. Four more
bills are expected to pass the third reading, according to the
president.
</P>
<P>
In the early hours of July 1 after the swearing-in ceremony,
the legislative body is going to have three readings of the
Reunification Act -- an arrangement to reaffirm all the previously
endorsed 13 bills before they become law.
</P>
<P>
The draft of the Reunification Act has not yet been made
public, but Fan expected that the Chief Executive's Office will
publish the draft in a day or two.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
