<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: US Increases Aid to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. will soon announce an aid
package of 100 million U.S. dollars to Jordan in addition to the
300 million dollar military assistance pledged by the Clinton
administration, the semi-official daily Jordan Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan, now in the U.S. on an official
visit, on Monday met Vice President Al Gore, who assured him that
"the 100 million additional aid package was American money - an
American concern," the English daily said.
</P>
<P>
However, when addressing the Washington Institute for Near East
Policy Monday, Hassan said that "it is coincidental that 100
million dollars (which the U.S. Congress allocated to move its
embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem) is almost equivalent
to the sum total of the aid package promised to Jordan, which of
course will not go down well at home."
</P>
<P>
According to local Arabic newspapers, both sides still have
differences as to what form the aid will take. The U.S. wants to
provide Jordan with 100 million dollars worth of equipment and
projects, whereas Jordan wants the aid in cash.
</P>
<P>
The differences are expected to be settled during Hassan's
current visit to the U.S., the papers said.
</P>
<P>
Whatever form it will take, equipment and projects or cash, the
aid package can without doubt contribute to the kingdom, which is
suffering from decreased foreign aid, reduced expatriates'
remittances and in effect an economy in recession.
</P>
<P>
Local financial markets have seemed encouraged and registered
sharp increases in trading volume on the news reports that the 100
million dollars is on the way and King Hussein won 60 million and
9 million dollars in grants from France and the Netherlands
respectively during his current European trip.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming money will help stabilize the kingdom, which
enjoys political importance because, among others, of its
geographical location and its efforts to bring the peace process
back on track.
</P>
<P>
Of course, the U.S. aid will help secure its own interests in
the Middle East region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
