<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Wheat Output to Drop, Others to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Australia's wheat output is
projected to drop in the coming year while outputs of wool, sugar,
meat and dairy products are expected to rise, according to an
official forecast released today.
</P>
<P>
Australia's wheat production would plummet by nearly a third in
the 1997/98 fiscal year (July 1, 1997-June 30, 1998) to 16.25
million tons, the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource
Economics (ABARE) said in its June quarter Commodities outlook.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said the outlook for Australian wool growers has
improved, with boosted demand, production and prices expected in
1997/98.
</P>
<P>
ABARE said demand would rise in 1997-98 as a result of higher
economic growth in key wool-consuming countries, such as the
United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
"This higher demand, coupled with little change in Australian
supply to the market, is forecast to result in an increase in the
eastern market indicator to average 650 Australian cents each kg
for the year," it said .
</P>
<P>
Australia's total wool production would rise to 688 kilotons in
1997/98 compared to the expected 682 kt the current financial year
ending June 30 and 697 kt in 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
It said abundant water and ideal weather conditions contributed
to a forecast record cotton production for 1996/1997.
</P>
<P>
"Harvesting is nearing completion and production is estimated
to be 2.7 million bales, eclipsing the previous record of 2.2
million bales set in 1991/92," the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
"The volume of exports increased in 1996/97 and is forecast to
rise again in 1997/98."
</P>
<P>
"The value of exports in both years is forecast to exceed 750
million US dollars."
</P>
<P>
The bureau said sugar production is tipped to rise from 4.9
million tons in 1995/96 to 5.4 million tons in 1996/97 and 5.6
million tons in 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the widespread destruction to the crop caused by
Cyclone Justin (earlier this year), Australian sugar production is
forecast to increase in 1997/98 from an increased harvest area".
</P>
<P>
The bureau said total beef and veal production was seen rising
to 1.73 million tons in the coming financial year compared to 1.66
million tons in 1996/97.
</P>
<P>
Australian meat producers could expect higher returns in
1997/98 as production by the main competitor, the United States,
contracts.
</P>
<P>
Australian milk production was forecast to rise 3.8 percent in
1997/98, following an estimated 3.3 percent increase in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
But ARABE warned the prospect of poor pasture conditions in
1997/98 would hit milk output.
</P>
<P>
Strong international demand was expected to push Australia's
dairy export earnings up by almost 13 percent in 1997/98 to 1.42
billion US dollars from 1.27 billion US dollars from the previous
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
