<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Minister Hails New EU Budget Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
hailed the budget stability pact reached Monday at the European
Union (EU) summit in Amsterdam, the Netherlands, saying "there are
no losers" from the compromised result, a German newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The budget pact, designed to reinforce the credibility of the
planned single European currency which is scheduled to be launched
in 1999, was endorsed on the first day of the EU leaders' two-day
negotiations on a new EU treaty to modernize the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
In a interview with the German daily General Anzeiger, Waigel,
a main backer of the stability pact, said he was happy that there
had been no changes to the pact, which would create the conditions
for the 1999 launching of the single currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The French Socialist government eventually dropped its
resistance to the deal after other EU leaders agreed to couple it
with a resolution promising fresh efforts to combat unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The stability pact, aimed to ensure an Euro as strong as the
German mark, foresees huge fines for members joining the single
currency if they have budget deficits above 3 percent of gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
While noting that Germany did make efforts to take into
consideration the French concerns over employment, Waigel said
that what has been agreed upon in Amsterdam on the job issue was a
compromise which did not include binding commitments.
</P>
<P>
The job resolution fell short of France's demand to use the
excess reserves of the European Investment Bank (EIB) and the
European Coal and Steel Community to fund new European employment
programs, and merely called on the EIB to consider new lending
possibilities, including a venture-capital fund for high-tech
industries and loans for education, health, the environment and
urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
Waigel said the resolution conformed to the German position and
job creation remains a national responsibility.
</P>
<P>
"There will be stronger coordination of the national measures
(on job creation). But there will be no new spending and
responsibility for the EU," Waigel said.
</P>
<P>
He also assured that Germany would not pump additional money
into new European job programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
