<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Condemn IRA Killing of Policemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- European Union leaders today
condemned the killing of two Northern Irish policemen by the Irish
Republic Army (IRA) on Monday and extended their sympathy to the
victims' families.
</P>
<P>
"The European Union heads of state and government meeting in
Amsterdam have heard with horror of the murder of two policemen by
the provisional IRA in Northern Ireland...," the leaders said in a
statement which was issued at their two-day summit here.
</P>
<P>
"They condemn this callous act of terrorism and extend their
deepest sympathy to the families of the victims," the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
Two Northern Ireland policemen were killed Monday near Belfast,
capital of Northern Ireland. The IRA, who has been fighting for
an end to British rule over Northern Ireland in the past 28 years,
immediately claimed responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair today repeated his
condemnation of the IRA, saying that the ambush was designed to
derail peace efforts. On Monday after the killing, he ruled out
any fresh meeting between government officials and the IRA's
political wing, Sinn Fein.  
</P>
</TEXT>
