<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Protest Against Turkish Violations of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus government will lodge
protest to the United Nations over the fresh violations of its
airspace and territorial waters by Turkish aircraft and navy
vessels.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing here today, Government
Spokesman Manolis Chistofides said 16 Turkish F-16 fighter
aircraft violated Nicosia Flight Information Region (FIR) on June
15 and 16.
</P>
<P>
He also confirmed the earlier reports on the presence of
Turkish navy vessels in the ports of the Turkish-controlled
northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
According to the Turkish Cypriot press today, a total of nine
Turkish navy vessels have dropped anchor in the ports of
Turkish-occupied Kyrenia and Famagusta, on the island's northern
and the eastern coasts.
</P>
<P>
Among them, two Turkish frigates, two submarines and one
destroyer have docked in Famagusta port. In Kyrenia harbor,
there are three missile boats and one submarine. Their presence
was also confirmed by the Cypriot Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the Turkish vessels have docked in the
two ports after taking part in the Turkish seaborne military
exercise "Sea Wolf '97" and will remain there until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Government Spokesman noted that official protests will be
lodged with the United Nations for all violations.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island has been divided into the Greek
Cypriot south and the Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when
Turkish troops occupied its northern third in the wake of a
short-lived pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Nine years after the division of the island, the Turkish
Cypriot side established a breakaway state "The Turkish Republic
of Northern Cyprus", which is recognized only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
