<HEADLINE> Boulmerka Withdraws from Mediterranean Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Former Olympic gold medalist Hassiba
Boulmerka pulled out of the 13th Mediterranean Games in Bari,
Italy on Tuesday after injuring her leg in training, according to
reports from Bari.
</P>
<P>
Amar Brahmia, head of the Algerian delegation, said: "She has a
problem with her leg. She is in a training camp in Germany and her
doctor informed us. It's a recurring problem."
</P>
<P>
Boulmerka won a gold medal at the Barcelona Olympics in
1992 but pulled out of the 1,500 meter finals at Atlanta last year
after a bad fall.
</P>
<P>
Dionisio Ciccarese, communications director of the
Mediterranean Games, said the poor turn-out of leading athletes
was because regional events were being hit by the bigger cash-rich
international meetings.
</P>
<P>
He added that the tight schedule running up to the world
championships in two months meant long-distance runners could not
be expected to also compete at Bari.
</P>
<P>
After the third day of competition in 27 sports, Italy led the
medal table with 20 golds. Turkey was in second place with 14
golds and France third with 12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
