<HEADLINE> France Says Libreville Meeting "Insufficient" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- France today described as
"insufficient" the nine-hour mediation meeting on the crisis of
the Republic of Congo held Monday in Libreville, Gabon.
</P>
<P>
"It could be difficult to be otherwise with so little time,"
said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that France encourages the international
mediation committee to continue making initiatives to help foster
rapprochement between the warring parties.
</P>
<P>
He said first measures to be taken by the Congolese should be
the arrangement of a cease-fire, which would "make up a solid
basis for the return of confidence."
</P>
<P>
Fighting began on June 5 when government troops surrounded the
home of former president Denis Sassou N'Guesso in a crackdown on
private militias and unauthorized arms in the runup to the July 27
election.
</P>
<P>
A number of African leaders, headed by Gabonese President Omar
Bongo, talked with the envoys of President Pascal Lissouba and
Sassou N'Guesso for nine hours to seek a solution to the crisis of
the country. But no agreements were reached.
</P>
<P>
Fighting resumed today in the Congolese capital of Brazzaville
between government troops and the "Cobras" militiamen of Sassou
N'Guesso, the Agence France-Presse news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
President Lissouba has made "a strident appeal to the French
people" to help him out, as French troops are leaving the country
after completing its "Pelican Operation" for evacuating foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Congo was a former colony of France.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the French daily "La Croix," Lissouba
accused French President Jacques Chirac of "abandoning and
rejecting" him.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed the French oil group Elf-Acquitaine, which
produces 80 percent of the oil products of Congo, for doing
nothing while his country was plunged into "blood and fire."
</P>
<P>
Followers of Sassou N'Guesso said today that Lissouba asked
France for help because he was "afraid of failing."
</P>
<P>
"When Mr Lissouba launched a strident appeal to French
soldiers... maybe he is unaware that there does not exist a
military agreement between France and Congo," said a radio serving
Sassou N'Guesso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
