<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Accidents Claim 44 Lives in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Some 44 people were killed and 48
severally injured in two separate accidents in Iran, a press
report said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Persian daily Hamshahri reported that the first accident
occurred near Eshtehard, some 70 kilometers west of the capital
city of Tehran, at 7 a.m. Monday morning. Some 35 passengers were
 killed and 41 people were injured as two buses collided.
</P>
<P>
Quoting an eyewitness, the daily said that both bus drivers
were killed on the spot. He added that the accident occurred as
one of the buses tried to overtake a vehicle on the road without
observing the traffic rules.
</P>
<P>
A local official said that the injured were in critical
condition and warned that the casualties may rise. The injured
are hospitalized in Tehran and Karaj, a city some 46 kilometers
west of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The second accident occurred in southwestern Iran near
Afghanistan border, some 80 kilometers south of the border city of
Zabol, on Sunday, according to the Persian daily Jomhuri Islami.
</P>
<P>
Nine people were killed and seven injured as the driver
of Toyota pickup truck who had fallen asleep veered to the
left side of the road and collided with a bus.
</P>
<P>
The injured have been taken to hospitals in Zabol and
Zahedan, provincial capital of Sistan and Baluchistan.
</P>
<P>
In a move to check accidents and lower the casualties resulting
from collisions, Iranian authorities have announced that starting
June 22, the fines for major traffic violations including illegal
speeding and violating the lane that belongs to the incoming
traffic will be increased by 500 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
