<HEADLINE> Agriculture Remains Top Cash Earner in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's agriculture recorded a
four-percent growth rate last year, the third consecutive year
for increase, with tea production jumping to the number one in the
world for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The rise is due to the stability of the economy, coupled with
better output of coffee, tea, sugarcane, wheat and horticultural
produce, said the official 1996 Economic Survey.
</P>
<P>
Coffee yield shoot up by 7.7 percent from 95,800 tons in 1995
to 103,200 tons last year, the Daily Nation newspaper quoted the
survey as reporting today.
</P>
<P>
Wheat production went up by five percent from 128,600 tons in
1995 to 135,000 tons in 1996. However, the yield fell below the
domestic requirement, entailing the importation of 485,000 tons
during the year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of fresh horticultural produce mounted by 18 percent
from 71,800 tons in 1995 to 84,800 tons last year, earning the
country a total of 7.7 billion Shillings (142.6 million U.S.
Dollars) in foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Cut flower exports recorded a 20-percent increase in 1996
compared with 1995. Export of mangos to the Middle East almost
doubled to 4,245 tons last year as a result of better farming
methods.
</P>
<P>
The major handicaps to horticultural development remains the
supply of high quality seeds, especially beans, slow added value
tax refunds and poor infrastructure, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
However, the production of maize and beans dropped because of
poor rains, driving market prices up. enditem

