<HEADLINE> Libya to Host 9th African Information Ministers' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Libya will host the next conference
of African Ministers of Information in 1999, according to a
decision adopted at the 8th session of the ministers' meeting
which opened here this morning.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 24 African information ministers and a dozen of
chief delegates to the inaugural session unanimously approved
Libya's request to host the forthcoming conference.
</P>
<P>
The request was forwarded by Libyan Secretary of Information
Fawziya Shalaby.
</P>
<P>
During the ministers' first working session held closed-door
this morning, a number of topics tabled on the agenda was
endorsed, including the reports on African media and information
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the participants stressed the importance of holding
bi-annual meetings especially that the "current unstable
conditions in the continent require continued consultations among
the African information ministers."
</P>
<P>
There were suggestions at the previous meeting in Cape Town,
South Africa in 1995 that the conference should be held every four
years, instead of two years.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif, chairman of the
conference, asserted in his inaugural address the importance of
keeping abreast of rapid technological development to establish a
African T.V. and radio channel as well a communication system.
</P>
<P>
Discussions on setting up regional information and
communication ventures and tackling challenges facing the African
development will top the agenda of the African information
ministers in their three-day meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
