<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Marks World Day to Combat Desertification, Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of tourists gathered
today at the Badaling section of the Great Wall to mark the third
UN-designated World Day to Combat Desertification and Drought.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the National Greening Committee, the Ministry of
Forestry and the Beijing Municipal People's Government were
present.
</P>
<P>
Similar activities have been held for the past month in other
major cities in China, involving about 1.1 million people across
the country, according to the Ministry of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Forestry Xu Youfang said "We hope this will help
spread the knowledge of desertification among Chinese citizens
and raise public awareness about the need to combat
desertification.
</P>
<P>
A 1,997-meter long scroll with more than one million signatures
of Chinese people will be sent to the UN conference on fighting
desertification, scheduled for September, according to the
Ministry of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey shows that 27.3 percent of China's total land
suffers from desertification, and the area of desertified land is
spreading by 2,460 sq km yearly.
</P>
<P>
To hasten the desertification efforts, China has initiated a
series of ecological improvement plans, such as the "Three Norths"
shelterbelt systems project, the world's largest ecological
endeavor, which covers the north, northeast and northwest, Xu told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, the first and second phases of the "Three Norths"
project were successfully completed and the third phase begun, Xu
said, adding that the project has increased the forest coverage in
the three northern areas from 5.05 percent 20 years ago to the
present nine percent.
</P>
<P>
"A 'green wall' has been basically formed in this area, putting
20 percent of the sandy land in the area under control," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that in addition to the recently-released
national report on desertification, China is now working on its
first law to combat desertification.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Gives Final Push for New Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- European Leaders, having put a
rift over the single currency behind them, are trying on Tuesday
at the Amsterdam summit to give a final push to conclude a new
treaty to prepare the 15-nation bloc for the next century.
</P>
<P>
After the talks of the heads of states and governments on
Monday, officials said most of the new treaty was already agreed
but major sticking points remained over such sensitive issues as
foreign and defense policy and EU's institutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
"There is broad agreement on many issues but unanimity on
none," Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini told reporters,
"There are some important questions still unresolved."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the leaders have defused the tension between France
and Germany, the major engine behind the European integration, on
the single currency by reaching a compromise in which Germany gets
guarantees that strict budget rules will be maintained and France
gets a non-binding pledge to fight unemployment.
</P>
<P>
On the treaty talks, some EU sources said that the
negotiations held during a dinner on Monday night "went pretty
badly."
</P>
<P>
A draft treaty prepared by the Dutch EU presidency and now
being under discussion by the EU leaders, is the culmination of 15
months of negotiations, formally dubbed the Inter-governmental
Conference.
</P>
<P>
The modest text seems to have dashed the high hopes expressed
earlier on in the Treaty renegotiating process.
</P>
<P>
It is likely to be watered down by adding to it a series of opt
outs and protocols.
</P>
<P>
On institutional reforms, Britain, France and Germany want to
enhance their influence within the Union, but the Dutch draft
treaty, bowing to the pressure of small states, more or less puts
off any reform to the EU and its institutions until the next wave
of enlargement.
</P>
<P>
As for foreign policy issue, six countries -- France, Germany,
Belgium, Luxembourg, Italy and Spain -- have called for the
incorporation into the Treaty of the objective of an eventual
merger of the European defense club the Western Union into the EU
and the introduction of a Protocol defining the stages of and
strategy for this merger.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch text merely alluded to the Protocol, because Britain,
supported by the "neutral" member states, is opposed to the idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
