<HEADLINE> 60 Iraqi Kurds Arrested for illegal Entry in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Iranian authorities said that they
have arrested 60 Iraqi Kurds in western and southern Iran after
they entered illegally in search of jobs and economic opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Persian daily Kar-O-Karegar today quoted security sources as
saying that the Iraqi Kurds were from the Sulaymaniyah city in
Iraqi Kurdistan.
</P>
<P>
"The Iraqi Kurds were caught in such Iranian cities as
Zahedan, Salmas, Bonab, Divandarreh, Sanandaj, Saqqez and Qeshm
Island in the Persian Gulf," the security sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that those who were arrested admitted that
they entered Iranian territory to find jobs because of
economic hardships and the unstable political situation in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The daily reported that those arrested were deported back
to Iraq after going through the legal steps here in Iran.
</P>
<P>
The factional fighting between pro-Iranian Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) and pro-Baghdad Kurdistan's Democratic Party (KDP)
has destabilized the economy in Iraqi Kurdistan, forcing many of
the Kurdish youth to seek employment in other neighboring countries
including Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
