<HEADLINE> China, Australia Sign Documents on Cattle Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China and Australia signed here
today two quarantine documents concerning China's import of
Australia's live cattle, other animals and their products, which
could open a new market for Australia's beef producers.
</P>
<P>
The two documents include a protocol on quarantine and
sanitation conditions of Australia's live cattle and a memorandum
of understanding on anthrax quarantine of Australia's animals and
their products to be exported to China.
</P>
<P>
The two documents were signed this afternoon by Wang Dahai,
director of the Plant and Animal Quarantine Bureau as
representative of the Chinese Ministry of Agriculture, and Paul
Barrantt, director of the Australian Quarantine Inspection Service
as representative of the Primary Industries and Energy Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Wang said the protocol is the first of its kind China has
signed with a foreign country on large-scale import of live
cattle.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum involves such animals as cattle, sheep, horses
and pigs.
</P>
<P>
Australia's national newspaper The Australian said today that
the deal is seen by the beef industry as an important step toward
removing long-standing Chinese concerns about disease in
Australian cattle, especially the blue tongue disease in northern
Australia, and could open a new live-cattle market for embattled
beef producers in the country.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the deal is likely to see up to 60,000 head of
Australian cattle shipped to China "in the near future."  
</P>
</TEXT>
