<HEADLINE> Britain Satisfied With Treaty Enabling Border Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The British government is
satisfied that the new Amsterdam Treaty leaves certain member
states of the European Union (EU) to exercise control of their
borders, British officials said today.
</P>
<P>
"We are allowed to keep doing what we want in this field,"
officials said, "We have reached an agreement on this."
</P>
<P>
EU leaders are holding a summit in Amsterdam to try to work out
a new treaty for bloc in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Border control is one of the key issues in the rewrite of the
EU treaty designed to prepare the bloc for new member states from
the east.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair has repeatedly stated that
there would be no surrender of control over Britain's borders,
mainly involving immigration and rights of asylum.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that Blair remains opposed to the incorporation
of the Western European Union (WEU), Europe's fledgling defense
arm, into the EU, fearing that the WEU may undermine the position
of NATO.
</P>
<P>
The idea of gradual EU-WEU merger, supported by some EU states
including France and Germany, is also resisted by EU's five
neutral nations which do not wish to get involved in large
international military operations.
</P>
<P>
Ten of the 15 EU states except Austria, Denmark, Finland,
Ireland and Sweden, are WEU members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
