<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Strong Growth in HK's Communications Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's communications
industry registered strong growth in 1995, according to figures in
a survey which was released here today by the Census and
Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed an increase of 18 percent in value terms over
1994 in the industry's total receipts, i.e. business receipts and
other income.
</P>
<P>
And a moderate growth was recorded in the total receipts in the
insurance, storage and business services, with increases of 11, 10
and seven percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The financing (except banking) industry registered a decrease
of eight percent in the total receipts over 1994.
</P>
<P>
These are some of the major findings of the 1995 Survey of
Storage, Communications, Financing, Insurance and Business
Services, which was conducted from May 1996 to early 1997.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, there were some 690 establishments operating in the
communications industry, an increase of 11 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The total receipts generated by these establishments amounted
to 47 billion HK dollars (6.02 billion U.S. dollars), which was 18
percent higher than 1994.
</P>
<P>
The total operating expenditure of the industry amounted to
64.6 percent of the total receipts, which was 0.5 percentage point
above the 1994 figure.
</P>
<P>
The total value added of these establishments was 18 percent
high than 1994.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500 establishments in operation in the insurance industry
in 1995 generated total receipts of 46 billion HK dollars (5.89
billion U.S. dollars), which represented an increase of 11 percent
over 1994.
</P>
<P>
The total receipts generated by the 310 establishments in the
storage industry amounted to five billion HK dollars (0.64 billion
U.S. dollars) , a 10 percent increase over 1994 and the total
value added of the industry increased by 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 23,200 establishments in the business services industry in
operation in 1995 generated total receipts of 70 billion HK
dollars (8.97 U.S. dollars), an increase of seven percent over
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
