<HEADLINE> US Assures Commitment to Gulf Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said his country will continue to commit itself to Gulf
security by maintaining a strong military presence in the region
to face what he called threats from Iran and Iraq, according to
news reaching here today from Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
"We stressed our commitment to maintaining the region's
security and we will continue to keep strong and enough military
capabilities." the Bahraini news agency quoted Cohen as saying.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference held in Bahrain this morning before his
departure for the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Cohen said the
military capabilities are able to "protect our warships and
interests" of the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that all of the countries in the region are currently
reliant on the U.S. presence with around 20,000 troops deployed
there for their security arrangements, and he expected these
countries would be able to contribute to the security in the
future.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. troops will remain in the region so as to strengthen
its relations with its Gulf allies, and his country will honor its
long-term commitment to the region's security, Cohen added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some Gulf countries are seeking to develop
their defense system by upgrading and purchasing advanced weapons
that U.S. troops possess. U.S. supports the desire, he said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the military of the Gulf states will work shoulder to
shoulder with the U.S. troops in the future.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived in Bahrain Monday, the third leg of his first
tour of Gulf region as defense secretary. He had visited Saudi
Arabia and Kuwait, and would travel to the UAE and Oman, before
flying home Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Iran and Iraq, the U.S. official said that his
country still regards the two as threats to the region, and
Washington will continue to pursue tough policies towards them.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Iran and Iraq are still "violating international
rules and regulations," and refuse "obedience to U.N. decisions
and store weapons of massive destruction" has clearly shown that
they are threatening peace and stability in the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also accused Iran of continuing to support international
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. still endorses the policy to maintain the U.N.
sanctions against Iraq until Baghdad complies with all the U.N.
resolutions adopted during the 1990-1991 Gulf crisis and the
collapse of the rule by Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen explained that the recent U.S. Congress resolution
justifying Jerusalem as Israel's "undivided capital" was not the
opinion of the U.S. administration.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives passed the non-binding resolution
Tuesday and set aside 100 Million dollars to move the U.S. embassy
from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem. This sparked criticism from the Arab
world and renewed violence in the occupied Arab lands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
