<HEADLINE> China Tightens Rein On Extra-Budgetary Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China will step up its annual
review of extra-budgetary funds this year to standardize their
management, a senior financial official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The official examination of extra-budgetary funds between early
June and late August this year has got off to a good start in
some provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions, according
to Jin Lianshu, a Ministry of Finance official in charge of the
check-up.
</P>
<P>
Jin said this year's examination of extra-budgetary funds will
focus primarily on units in the public security sector, in
industrial and commercial administration and in the system for
civil affairs administration.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is aimed at establishing and improving the
management system of extra-budgetary funds and tightening
supervision over the collecting and spending of such funds, Jin
said.
</P>
<P>
Last year's examination of extra-budgetary funds was highly
successful, uncovering 34.5 billion yuan of wrongly collected
funds and 10.2 billion yuan of wrongly spent funds, and checking
corruption by penalizing officials caught in illegal activities
involving extra-budgetary funds, Jin said.
</P>
<P>
But problems still remain in the funds' management, which calls
for this year's review to come up with the answers, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 check-up will mainly deal with problems such as
illegal charging of fees, unauthorized funds, mismanagement of
extra-budgetary funds, and illegal spending of the funds, Jin
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
