<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Focus of the Lenses by Xu Xingtang, Chang Kefei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- It is hot here these days -- due
not only to the sweltering weather that makes reporters dripping
with sweat, but also the pre-handover atmosphere that has the
attention of the whole world focused on Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With less than two weeks to go before Hong Kong's return to
China, more than 8,000 journalists who applied to cover the
historic occasion have been flying in from every corner of the
globe.
</P>
<P>
The world is keen to know what is going on in Hong Kong. What
will the reporters tell the world?
</P>
<P>
"The handover ceremony will be the top subject of our
coverage," said Fok Yit Wai, a reporter from Singapore.
</P>
<P>
This is a common view held by nearly all the 700-plus media
organizations joining this media battle of the century. In fact,
all major events scheduled to take place between June 30 and July
1 will be of great interest, such as the handover ceremony, the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region inauguration ceremony, the
July 1 meeting of the Hong Kong Provisional Legislative Council
and the British withdrawal ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the dominant scenario, every contender in the media
competition will focus on its own particular fields. "We'll pay
attention to common people's feelings and reactions about the
handover," said Fok Yit Wai. "Over 8,000 Singaporeans are working
in Hong Kong, and we are interested in their opinions about Hong
Kong's return to its motherland."
</P>
<P>
Chief Editor of AFP Hong Kong Bureau Richard Ingham said his
agency has an ambitious program of advance coverage, including
features and analyses of Hong Kong at the moment, and predictions
about what Hong Kong will be after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Toine Berbers from De Volkskrant, a major Dutch newspaper,
said: "During the handover, I will focus my attention on whether
China will stick to its 'one country, two systems' promise. I've
made many interviews and spoken to many people."
</P>
<P>
Commenting that all over the world places which were once
subjected to colonial rule have been returned to their peoples, he
said, "I think the handover of Hong Kong to China is only natural
and should have taken place much earlier. I hope it will go
smoothly because it is important both for Hong Kong and for
China," he said.
</P>
<P>
CNN International announced an ambitious plan for coverage of
the handover as early as in April, saying that it will present
in-depth analyses of the historic event in addition to live,
extensive coverage immediately preceding and following the
handover.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for CNN International said: "We try to cover the
handover in a comprehensive and global perspective, and explore
its impact and implications for Hong Kong, China, Asia and the
rest of the world."
</P>
<P>
The cable network has already broadcast a series of special
reports on Hong Kong, such as "Hong Kong one year and counting"
and "Hong Kong, Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
Goran Leijonhufvud, who has been living in Hong Kong since 1989
as a reporter for Sweden's largest morning daily Dagens Nyheter,
said his paper will invite a group of readers to Hong Kong at the
end of June to witness this historic moment.
</P>
<P>
He said he did not agree with the ideas of a Fortune magazine
cover story in 1995 entitled "Death of Hong Kong." "Ninety-five
percent of western reporters stationed in Hong Kong would say that
the argument is wrong," he said.
</P>
<P>
In his eyes, most Hong Kong people are confident about their
future.
</P>
<P>
A phenomenon that should be noticed is that journalists from
western countries and those from Asian countries have quite
different stresses in their coverage.
</P>
<P>
AFP's Richard Ingham said it is a difference of ways to
interpret the same issues. A western reporter is likely to put
emphasis on freedom of expression, freedom of assembly and other
values and rights popular in the West, while a reporter from a
developing country tends to stress the fundamentals of human
progress and economic aspects.
</P>
<P>
"To a large extent, this disparity is related to cultural
background and economic development," he said, admitting that
there are people who come to Hong Kong with prejudices and fixed
ideas and who know nothing about the place and the people.
</P>
<P>
Kieu Tinh, who came to Hong Kong last year to open the Hong
Kong Office of Vietnam News Agency, said his major task was to
present an overall picture of Hong Kong to the Vietnamese people.
</P>
<P>
"I've interviewed civil servants and bankers, and talked with
people in the street, and I found that most of them believe Hong
Kong will have a bright future," he said. "Things here are quite
different from those depicted in some western reports."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
