<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: Palestinian-Israeli Gap Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said today that gap remained between the Palestinian and Israeli
sides despite intensive efforts to remove obstacles to resuming
the deadlocked peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after President Hosni Mubarak reviewed the
latest developments of the Mideast peace process and discussed his
upcoming tour to France during a meeting held earlier today with
Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, his political advisor Osama
el-Baz and Moussa.
</P>
<P>
"There is still a gap regarding the Middle East peace process
but Egyptian efforts are underway to change the situation," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have deadlocked for three
months since Israel broke ground on a new Jewish settlement in
East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent U.S. threat to block aid to the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and the Congress decision to
move the American Embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem, Moussa
described it as an unwise decision that contradicts the bases of
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
But he added that it was counterbalanced by a U.S. State
Department statement Monday that reaffirmed the status of
Jerusalem is open to negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's intensified diplomacy brokered the meeting in three
months between the Palestinian and Israeli negotiations in Cairo
on June 8 but failed to bring them together for a second round due
to big rifts upon the Jewish settlement issues.
</P>
<P>
The main obstacle to new substantive talks is the disagreement
over Israeli settlement activity, especially in Arab East
Jerusalem, which is claimed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
"Some sort of continuity is required to deal with many problems
mainly the settlements issue," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
In Egypt's latest contacts with the parties, Moussa and Baz met
with PNA Minister of Local Administration at Saeb Erekat.
</P>
<P>
Moussa ruled out another imminent shuttle tour by Baz to bring closer
viewpoints of the Palestinians and Israelis and denied that Egypt
harbors any specific proposals to revive the peace process.
</P>
<P>
But he said freezing the construction of settlements for a
reasonable period would "help and go in line with resumption of
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian decision makers' meeting today came before Mubarak
meets with his French counterpart Jacques Chirac in Paris on
Thursday to discuss the European role in the peace process and the
settlements issue.
</P>
<P>
Moussa will also begin a European tour on Wednesday to Rome,
Paris and London for talks on Egyptian efforts exerted on the
European scene to push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
A French draft prepared for the upcoming European Union summit
in Amsterdam declares the willingness of the EU along with the
U.S. and Egypt to help promote a resumption of talks between
Israel and the PNA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
