<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese and Malaysian Premiers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohammed started his official activities on the second day of
his visit in Lebanon Tuesday with talks with Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri in the presence of senior officials from both
countries.
</P>
<P>
The official Lebanon Radio said that the Lebanese-Malaysian
talks in the Beirut Governmental Palace "ended up this morning
with the political, economic and diplomatic relations between
the two countries being consolidated."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir and Hariri held a half-an-hour closed-door meeting
at the beginning, in which "they reviewed the bilateral
relations and completed what they had discussed during the
Lebanese premier's visit to Malaysia in 1995," the state-owned
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Then the two heads of government presided an enlarged meeting
which was attended by Malaysian Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi and his Lebanese counterpart Farez Boueiz and
other governmental ministers of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting dealt with issues "to which the Malaysian side
expressed concern, including the dispatch of a Malaysian
ambassador to Lebanon and the establishment of a Malaysian
trade representative office in Beirut."
</P>
<P>
"The Malaysian side also expressed its interests in the
Lebanese projects of roads and civil air-navigation and an
enhancement of air communication between the two countries, in
addition to an activation of trade between them," the
radio said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed an agreement on the setup of an agency
for Malaysian-made cars in Lebanon to make Lebanon the center
for marketing Malaysian cars and other industrial products in
the region, the radio announced.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese officials briefed their Malaysian counterparts
the projects which Lebanon is executing as well as the country's
ambition, and "explained to the Malaysian side that they not
only want to obtain foreign investments, but also need to learn
Malaysia's experience in developing medium and light
industries," the report added.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, the Lebanese side also put forward the
possibility of establishing Malaysian-Lebanese joint ventures in
various sectors, especially in industry and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Following the meetings, the Malaysian premier inspected sites
of reconstruction projects in central Beirut and visited
SOLIDERE, a company which, as the brainchild of the billionaire
Prime Minister Hariri, is in charge of the rebuilding and
developing the commercial district in Beirut's downtown.
</P>
<P>
At a banquet he held in honor of the visiting Malaysian
premier Monday night, the Lebanese prime minister said his
government wants to encourage Malaysian businessmen to invest in
Lebanon's hotel sector and establish joint industrial projects
with Lebanese businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Hariri spoke highly of Malaysia's achievements in attaining
"the highest level of international competitiveness in trade,
industry and services" since Mahathir took office in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir believed that "Lebanon will rise again," noting that
"the remarkable recovery currently underway is a testimony of
Lebanon's indomitable spirit."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir arrived here Monday afternoon for the first visit of
a Malaysian head of government to this country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
