<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tribute to Deng Xiaoping's Contribution to Hong Kong's Return -- Xinhua Commentary (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During his meeting with guests from Hong Kong in June 1984, he
expounded the "one country, two systems" concept. When he met with
Britain's Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs
Geoffery Howe in July of the same year, he discussed five possible
situations that China did not want to see happen during the
transition period. But, he also pointed out that China would be
prepared for possible contingencies. His foresight in this was
later proven by the developments in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Hong Kong and Macao compatriots attending
National Day celebrations in Beijing in October 1984, he discussed
his thoughts about the maintenance of prosperity and stability in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In December of the same year, he again met with Prime Minister
Thatcher, who came to Beijing for the signing of the Sino-British
Joint Declaration. Earlier in 1982, he had stated that China would
only wait for one or two years before resuming its exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong but this could not be put off
indefinitely. So, the two countries completed their talks on the
Hong Kong issue according to his timetable.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Deng Xiaoping paid special attention to the
drafting of the Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with members of the Drafting Committee for the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR who were attending its ninth
plenary session in February 1990, he praised the basic law as a
creative masterpiece with historical significance and profound
importance for humanity. He warmly thanked the committee members for
their work and congratulated them on the document.
</P>
<P>
Deng's penetrating theoretical exposition of the "one country,
two systems" principle and the guidelines and policies that he
formulated for resolving the Hong Kong issue are our powerful
weapons to accomplish the great cause of reunification of the
motherland as well as our invaluable spiritual wealth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tribute to Deng Xiaoping's Contribution to Hong Kong' Return -- Xinhua Commentary (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Showing his deep love for the Hong Kong compatriots, he
said: "We are convinced that the Chinese in Hong Kong can run it
well. The distrust of the Chinese people's ability to run Hong
Kong well is the mentality left over from old colonialism."
</P>
<P>
He stated that the Hong Kong people have the sense of pride of
the Chinese nation and should have the self-confidence to manage
Hong Kong well.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's past prosperity was achieved by Hong Kong
residents with Chinese as the main body," he said. "The wisdom of
the Chinese is no inferior to foreigners'. The Chinese are not
incapable. We must not always think that only foreigners can do a
good job and we must believe that we Chinese can also do as well on
our own."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Hong Kong must be run by Hong Kong
residents with patriots as the main body and that others could
also be included.
</P>
<P>
According to Deng, the criteria for a patriot mean respect for
the nation, sincere support for the motherland's resumption of its
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong, and refrainment from
damaging Hong Kong's prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
Anyone who meets these criteria is a patriot, whether he
believes in capitalism, feudalism, or slavery, he said.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping's respect, trust and love of Hong Kong
compatriots and his bold political vision won the respect
of Hong Kong compatriots and benefited us greatly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
