<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Starts to Mark Special Bus Lanes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing Police Bureau
announced today it will open two-way lanes for buses only
beginning June 25 on Chang'an Avenue, the city's busiest downtown
thoroughfare which runs east-to-west for five kilometers.
</P>
<P>
This is just one step taken by the Chinese capital to solve the
problem of the city's traffic snarls.
</P>
<P>
The two-way lanes will be the first of their kind in China,
according to a notice issued by the Traffic Control Department of
the Police Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Each of the special bus lanes is at the far right lane of
traffic, and is marked with two lines of yellow dashes. Vehicles
other than buses and mini-buses which are approved by the police
departments are forbidden to enter these lanes.
</P>
<P>
Line-painting on the roads will be done after 10 p.m. when
traffic is light.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Beijing's roads can't keep up with the
demand of the increasing number of motor vehicles. In 1993, there
were 27 traffic-jam prone sites in the city; now there are
99. Every day, more than 50 traffic jams occur on the main streets
alone.
</P>
<P>
To encourage passengers to commute via public transportation so
as to ease traffic jams, Beijing has already adopted several
measures for the convenience of buses and the public, such as
increasing the number of bus stops and allowing buses to pass
across other vehicle lanes except the farthest left lane -- the
fast lane.
</P>
<P>
According to police surveys, about 500 vehicles travel Chang'an
Avenue per hour, and more than 340,000 passengers per day.
</P>
<P>
"The special bus lanes on this avenue will help more of
Beijing's passengers enjoy the convenience and efficiency of
public transportation," a police official said.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that after the opening of the special bus lanes,
bus speeds will be at least 15 percent faster.
</P>
<P>
Other such lanes are expected to be opened this year in other
major streets in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
