<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Celebrity Praises "One Country, Two Systems" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Ikuo Hirayama, president of
Japan-China Friendship Association, today spoke highly of China's
"one country, two systems" principle proposed by late Chinese
leader Deng Xiaoping for its great significance.
</P>
<P>
The principle is of great importance not only to China but also
to the whole world as it has set an example for countries which
could hardly resolve existing problems like the Hong Kong case
with only one system, Hirayama said in an interview with Xinhua at
his residence in Kamakura city, 45 kilometers southwest of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Hirayama described the principle as "a new truth" which is
unprecedented and reflects Deng's foresight and wisdom.
</P>
<P>
If it is successfully carried out, those countries will surely
follow suit, he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the "one country, two systems" principle, the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) will retain its present
economic and social systems at least for the next 50 years after
its return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
During the hour long interview, Hirayama also expressed his
belief that Hong Kong's prosperity and stability will be
maintained after the handover, for "a prosperous and stable Hong
Kong is in the interest of China."
</P>
<P>
Hirayama, who is also a well-known Japanese painter, said Hong
Kong, as an important center of arts, will help promote China's
arts exchanges with the outside world as a "window" after its
return to China.
</P>
<P>
Hirayama, who has visited China more than 50 times, has been
invited to go to Hong Kong to attend commemorating ceremonies
there by the Chinese government as one of the three distinguished
Japanese guests together with former Japanese Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita and Tomiichi Murayama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
