<HEADLINE> S. African Companies Make Investment in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of South African
engineering firms will join hands to build a sugar mill in Vietnam,
the local daily the Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture is worth 100 million U.S. dollars, of which
about one quarter would be handled by South African companies,
which include Flender Power Transmission, Siemens, Celcor and
Columbus, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There was a lot of interest in South Africa from Vietnam, and South
African businessmen's interest in Vietnam was also growing, Gustav
Meyer, Deputy Director for Export Promotion in the Trade and Industry
Department was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It's not an easy market, but it definitely has a lot of potential.
If we wait too long, we could be missing the boat," Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
According to South African Foreign Trade Organization, South
Africa last year exported goods worth 4.2 million U.S. dollars to
and imported goods worth 7.8 million dollars from Vietnam. enditem

=06171201

=06171218
NNNN
20:07 20:07 g # PAB
</P>
