<HEADLINE> More Ethnic Armed Group Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-five more members of the
Karen National Union (KNU), the last largest remaining
anti-government ethnic armed group in Myanmar, surrendered to the
government last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said today that the 25 men, headed by Saw Ba
La Htoo of the 10th Battalion of the KNU operating in the Dawei
area in Tanintharyi Division, "traded arms for peace" with the
local military authorities on June 15.
</P>
<P>
The KNU, one of the 16 ethnic armed groups in Myanmar, has been
active on the Myanmar-Thai border in armed opposition to the
government. It is also the last group which has not yet made peace
with the government although four rounds of peace talks have been
held.  
</P>
