<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Overall Labor Market Conditions Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's overall labor market
conditions remain generally stable in recent months, with both
unemployment and underemployment rates showing only marginal
change, a Hong Kong government spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was commenting on the latest labor force
statistics released here today by Hong Kong's Census and
Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted unemployment rate for the period
February - April 1997 was 2.6 percent, and the underemployment
rate was 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
For the period March - May 1997, the provisional seasonably
adjusted unemployment rate was slightly lower, at 2.5 percent,
while the provisional underemployment rate was slightly higher, at
1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that the decline in the unemployment rate
in the three-month period March - May 1997 was mainly concentrated
in the construction sector.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the other major sectors was generally stable.
As to the underemployment rate, slight increases occurred in the
construction and manufacturing sectors. The situation in the
other major sectors was likewise stable.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also pointed out that labor demand remained
robust amidst steady growth in the economy. In the three months
ending April 1997, total employment continued to grow
significantly, by 3.9 percent over a year earlier, faster than the
growth of 3.1 percent in total labor force.
</P>
<P>
During the period February - April 1997, the number of
unemployed persons was estimated at 73,000, and the number of
underemployed persons at 37,300.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment and underemployment statistics were obtained
from a continuous General Household Survey, in which the
definitions used in measuring unemployment and underemployment
follow closely those recommended by the International Labor
Organization.
</P>
<P>
Being "seasonably adjusted" refers to the fact that
unemployment rate has been adjusted for seasonal variations in the
proportion of first-time job-seekers in the labor force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
