<HEADLINE> Malaysian Court Upholds Death Sentence on Nigerians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Appeal Court in
Malaysia's northern state of Pulau Pinang today upheld the death
sentence imposed on three Nigerians found guilty of trafficking in
612.3 grams of heroin seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
Technician Adekunle Johnson Oshodi, 32, civil servant Tunde
Apatira and businessman Oladotun Lukmanu Umaru, both 35, were
charged with trafficking in 117.8 grams, 231.7 grams and 262.8
grams of the drug respectively, stuffed in 126 sausage-like
pallets and found in their stomachs when the trio were taken to
the Butterworth district hospital in the state on August 13, 1990.
</P>
<P>
They were sentenced to death by a high court in Pulau Pinang on
June 30, 1995, after they were found guilty under the Dangerous
Drugs Act 1952.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting their appeal against conviction and sentence, Appeal
Court Judge Shaik Daud Mohamed Ismail said today that the trial
judge had actually invoked the presumption (of possession and
knowledge) under Section 37A of the Dangerous Drugs Act in his
written judgment although he did not say so when delivering his
judgment, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
"We are also unanimously satisfied that the judge had carefully
considered the facts and are of the opinion that the comments he
made (during the trial) were to assess the evidence and not to
create an adverse inference of the case," Shaik Daud was quoted as
saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
