<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Says Africa Must Stand up to Prejudiced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African Unity
(OAU) today said Africa is increasingly falling prey to the power
of prejudiced propaganda, calling for Africa's awareness of the
importance of information.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the inaugural session of the Eighth Conference of
African Ministers of Information here this morning, OAU Secretary
General Salim Ahamed Salim pointed out that Africa has been
getting "unfair treatment from the foreign media tycoons."
</P>
<P>
Africa is represented in biased coverage, distortion of news
and projection of woes and negatives, he complained.
</P>
<P>
"We are portrayed in a way as if Africa is the only domain of
catastrophes in the world," he complained.
</P>
<P>
"As much as we were warning at the beginning of the 1990's
against the political and economical marginalization of Africa
in the post cold war era, it should be emphasized today that the
communication marginalization is more serious and threatening," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the deplorable situation on Africa's poor
communication and telecommunication infrastructure, lack of
adequate links and network as well as its inability to afford the
modern information technologies.
</P>
<P>
Terming information as the "strongest and most viable component
to the development process," the African leader criticized some
African governments for removing information sector from the
priority list of the national development plans.
</P>
<P>
Failure to realize the importance of information means Africa
"would remain passive impotent and recipient" in the international
information arena, he said.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief called upon the African nations to first
seriously put its disheveled information and communication house
in order.
</P>
<P>
The most urgent of all, he said, is to salvage the
financially-strapped Pan African News Agency (PANA), an
OAU-affiliated inter-governmental institution of news service, and
"give it a new orientation."
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to the meeting, Board of Directors
of the Dakar-based PANA has proposed selling 25 percent of its
capital to national news agencies of African countries and offer
the rest for private interests.
</P>
<P>
Discussions on setting up regional information and
communication ventures and tackling challenges facing the African
development will top the agenda of the three-day meeting of the 24
African information ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
