<HEADLINE> HK Government Briefs Journalists on Business, Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government today
hosted a panel briefing on "Investment Opportunities in Hong Kong"
for local and overseas journalists covering the Hong Kong handover
event.
</P>
<P>
The briefing was chaired by Director-General of Industry
Francis Ho, Chairman of the Hong Kong American Chamber of Commerce
Douglas Henck, and Michael Enright, visiting professor of Business
Administration at the University of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Francis Ho noted that Hong Kong enjoys a
unique economic environment, which finds expression in low taxes,
a rule of law and a free flow of capital and information.
</P>
<P>
"The upcoming historic return to China provides a good
opportunity for Hong Kong to develop its economy," he said. "I
believe that the government will not change its current hands-off
policy toward the economy after July 1."
</P>
<P>
Describing the Hong Kong economy as "one of the freest
economies in the world," Ho pointed out that Hong Kong has the
busiest shipping sector and the most significant stock market in
the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has also made great contributions to the
globalization process of the world economy," he added. "As the
gateway to the Chinese interior area, it is the most popular
location for foreign investment".
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that last year, Hong Kong brought in over 100
billion US dollars in foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Professor Enright, who has been in Hong Kong for years to study
the competitiveness of the Hong Kong economy, said that Hong Kong
has become a control center for manufacturing and service
industries throughout Asia,
</P>
<P>
"The future of Hong Kong is quite bright, because it is in the
interest of both China and the international investors to keep the
economic independence of Hong Kong," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that confidence has been expressed by both local and
overseas business communities, and many people who know Hong Kong
are placing their hopes on Hong Kong for the future.
</P>
<P>
Enright recently published a book titled "The Hong Kong
Advantage," in which he gave a detailed explanation to Hong Kong's
economic vitality and bright prospects.
</P>
<P>
According to Douglas Henck, Hong Kong possesses the first-class
civil service in the world, which has played a key role in its
economic success.
</P>
<P>
He said that the latest survey his chamber conducted among its
2,800 members showed that 95 percent of the respondents thought
that the business climate in Hong Kong would be "very favorable"
or "favorable" over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
"This has shown that the majority of American businessmen here
are optimistic about Hong Kong's future as a business center after
the handover," he concluded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
