<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher On Resources, Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A lower Australian dollar boosted
the resources sector and a strong banking sector pushed the
Australian sharemarket to another record closing today.
</P>
<P>
"A weaker Australian dollar is helping all the resource
stocks," Intersuisse equities manager Andrew Sekely said, adding
that the improvement in the gold price overnight had also been a
contributing factor.
</P>
<P>
Speculation that South African mining company Gencor Ltd. might
launch a 1.05 billion U.S. dollar takeover bid for nickel and
cobalt producer QNI Ltd. had also added value to the resources
sector, Sekely said.
</P>
<P>
QNI requested a trading suspension pending a board
announcement, fueling the takeover speculation. The bid would be
pitched at 3.4 Australian dollars (2.55 U.S. dollars) per share,
market players said.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries closed at another high of 2681.7, up 12.4
points, after reaching an intra-day high in early afternoon
trading of 2695.
</P>
<P>
BHP, the largest mining company in Australia, gained 40 cents
to 19.3 Australian dollars while Rio Tinto, another mining giant,
rose 58.7 cents to 23.195 Australian dollars and WMC 28 cents, or
3.39 percent, to 8.55 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, analysts said investors seeking higher
yields mainly in the Commonwealth Bank of Australia and continued
speculation about further bank rationalization drove the share
prices higher in morning and early afternoon trading, only to
taper off near the close.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank gained 19 cents to 15.19 Australian dollars,
National Australia Bank 7 cents to 18.85 Australian dollars and
Westpac 9 cents to 7.79 Australian dollars, but ANZ dropped 15
cents to 9.7 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index closed 19.5 points higher at 1518.3
while the All Industrials Index increased 5.8 points to 4194.9.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed down 9.6 points at 1529.1, with
Goldfields, Plutonic Resources, Ranger Minerals and Normandy all
falling.
</P>
<P>
Goldfields lost 8 cents, or 4 percent, to 1.92 Australian
dollars, Plutonic 8 cents to 4.6 Australian dollars and Ranger
Minerals 25 cents, or 5.26 percent, to 4.2 Australian dollars
while Normandy was down 1 cent to 1.62 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 420.56 million shares valued at 990.3
million Australian dollars (742.72 million U.S. dollars) with 615
falls and 595 rises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
