<HEADLINE> S. Africa Gets Loans from ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Abidjan-based African
Development Bank (ADB) has granted South Africa a loan of 25
million U.S. dollars to help pay for infrastructure projects,
local daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
The projects in the water, energy, transport and
telecommunications sectors are aimed at "developing some of the
basic infrastructure to help the worst off people", an official
of the bank was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
It is the first such loan to South Africa by the ADB,
following an "intense long-running consultation" between the bank
and South African governmental authorities, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Details of the interest rate and methods of repayment were not
yet finalized, according to the bank sources.
</P>
<P>
The African Development Bank is considering "the possibility
of granting credit lines to South African financial institutions"
in order to boost "several sectors of the economy", the bank
sources added.
</P>
<P>
The ADB, set up in July 1966, has 76 member states. It was
designed to offer necessary investment and loans to African
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
