<HEADLINE> Another Fire Breaks Out in Indian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Two floors of a multi-story
building housing several government and private offices on Janpath
Road of the city proper of New Delhi, capital of India, were
gutted in a fire today.
</P>
<P>
Thick smoke billowing out of the building enveloped the entire
area which was cordoned off by police. The top two floors of the
building were extensively damaged in the fire, yet there have been
no casualties reported so far.
</P>
<P>
More than 25 firemen were busy working to control the blaze,
the cause of which is yet to be ascertained. Deputy Chief Fire
Officer R.C. Sharma said electric short-circuit might have caused
the fire. It was reported that 89 high-rise buildings in the
capital are without the minimum fire safety equipment.
</P>
<P>
This is the third fire in the capital in the past one week.
Last Friday a blaze in Uphaar Cinema in South Delhi claimed 60
lives and two days later, a fire broke out in Kemkunt Towers in
the city but there were no casualties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
