<HEADLINE> Chinese Boomtown Aids Needy People in Other Parts of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China's first special economic
zone, Shenzhen, is doing a good job of providing funds to help
needy people elsewhere, as part of the country's efforts at common
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The boomtown set up an economic cooperation development fund in
1989, to promote economic growth in poor areas and loaned money at
half the banks' interest rate.
</P>
<P>
The fund has financed 146 poverty relief projects in other
parts of China with 575 million yuan. The projects are expected to
add 2.36 billion yuan in output value and 568 million yuan in
profits, upon completion.
</P>
<P>
The city invited more than 20 senior managers of large
enterprises to serve as advisers in selecting aid projects. It
spent 4.2 million yuan on a ferroalloy smelter to make use of the
rich hydropower resources in Jinggangshan, one of China's
revolutionary bases. As a result, the smelter brings 10,000 yuan
in profits every day on average.
</P>
<P>
The fund also provided 19.2 million yuan for resettling
villagers in the Three Gorges reservoir area.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen was asked by the State in 1995 to help Guizhou
Province, so the fund sent experts there, selected six key
projects, and provided 24 million yuan. The assistance is said to
have greatly helped the local economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
