<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coup Attempt to Topple S. Leone's Koroma Foiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- At least 10 military officers and
politicians were arrested on Monday in Freetown, capital of
Sierra Leone, for allegedly planning a counter-coup to overthrow
the three-week military junta.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here today, the officers
arrested included a major, two colonels and a lieutenant colonel.
They had reportedly suborned some members of the rebel
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) to oust Major Johnny Koroma who
took power in a coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 rebel troops of the RUF, which spearheaded the
civil war in the country in 1991, are known to have joined the
Sierra Leone army following the ouster of President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The six politicians arrested were said to be mainly ministers
under the civilian government led by Ahmed Tejan Kabbah toppled
in May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
Reports said heavily armed soldiers loyal to Koroma enhanced
security of the Pademba prison in Freetown, cordoning all roads
leading to it.
</P>
<P>
About 700 criminals escaped from the prison last month after
soldiers broke into the premises. Koroma who had earlier been put
in the same prison for alleged coup plot was freed by soldiers
who launched the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
The military junta headed by Johnny Koroma under a threat of
imminent attack by the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG)
have received wide-spread international condemnation even as they
seek to consolidate on their power through shuttling diplomacy in
some African countries to curry support.
</P>
<P>
it was reported that delegations sent by the military junta to
Cote d'Ivoire and Ghana were rebuffed by these countries who
demanded the unconditional restoration of President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
At home, civil servants defied the ruling junta's repeated
order to go back to work, continuing their peaceful strike, while
schools, shops, banks and other service facilities remained
closed.
</P>
<P>
Parliament members and religious leaders have also called on
the junta for returning power to civilians.  
</P>
</TEXT>
