<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Foreign Exchange Reserve Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) --Foreign exchange reserve in Nigeria
increased drastically in the first quarter of this year, hitting
5.9 billion U.S. dollars by March 31, from 4.086 billion dollars at
the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The latest figure is enough to pay for several months of imports,
local newspaper " This Day" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted finance ministry sources who attributed the sharp
reserve growth to proper management of the nation's foreign exchange
resources as well as positive effects of government's fiscal measures.
</P>
<P>
Higer foreign exchange reserve is believed to help a nation keep its
currency strong. But with the increase of reserve, the country's
currency has been depreciating at local market. The market rate
has changed from about 80 Naira to the dollar at the beginning of
this year to present 87 Naira or so.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the Nigerian government, instead of using the
reserve to meet exchange demand, might have applied substantial part of
the accumulated reserve to increasing funding for upstream (exploration)
and downstream (refining) oil sector which are said to be at the verge
of collapse due to inadequate funding.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
