<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cartoon Image of San Mao Estimated At 590 million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The most popular Chinese cartoon
of San Mao, with a shaven head and only three locks of hair on the
forehead and a bulb-like nose, was estimated to be worth 590
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The character was created in 1935 by the popular Chinese
cartoonist Zhang Leping and was immensely successful in the
cartoon strip "Urchin San Mao" which appeared in a Shanghai
newspaper from 1947 to 1948. The image of little San Mao stayed in
the memories of millions of Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The evaluation was made by the Shanghai Youlian Agency for
Assessing and Calculating Intangible Assets. The agency was one of
the first of its kind in Shanghai and has worked on several
cultural evaluations.
</P>
<P>
Chen Pengsheng, the head of the agency, says that the estimate
of value was based on several things like amount of publications,
degree of publicity, social impact, and various honors it won.
</P>
<P>
With the success of the strip, Zhang also produced a series of
other works involving San Mao, including "San Mao Past and
Present" and "San Mao Greets Liberation", with the founding of the
People's Republic of China in October of 1949.
</P>
<P>
'Urchin San Mao' has been appeared in many different art forms,
including films, TV dramas, and puppet shows. A feature film
entitled "Urchin San Mao" was shown on China Film Day at the
Cannes Film Festival and ran in six Paris cinemas for two months.
</P>
<P>
A special forum was organized in Shanghai on June 15 to mark
the 50th anniversary of "Urchin San Mao". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Lebanese government has approved a plan to set up
a company with 350-million-U.S.-dollar capital to finance and
construct about 100 kilometers of roads across Lebanon, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the Lebanon Toll Road Company's capital will
comprise 70 million shares -- each with a nominal value of five
dollars -- open for Lebanese and foreign subscription.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The International Finance Corporation (IFC) has
recently declared that Egypt is now qualified as one of the most
attracting investment markets and enlisted in the IFC investment
index, according to the latest issue of the Middle East News
Weekly.
</P>
<P>
IFC is the largest multilateral source of equity and loan
financing for private sector project in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The IFC investment index is considered among the key criteria
used to steer the allocation of foreign capital into investment
areas in promising markets. It now comprises 26 countries,
including three Arab countries of Jordan, Morocco and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Jordanian Minister of Industry, Trade and Finance Hani
Al-Moulki has said that Egypt and Jordan intend to establish a
free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted in the latest issue of the Middle East
News Weekly as saying that the issue will be discussed during
meetings of the joint higher committee between the two countries
which will meet in Cairo at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Agreements on increasing the trade exchange between the two
countries, prevention of dual taxation and investment protection
will be signed during the committee meetings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
