<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Int'l Treaties To Continue To Apply to HK: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 international
treaties will continue to apply to Hong Kong as of July 1, 1997,
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Cui Tiankai announced here
today at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Cui said the Chinese government has recently presented notes to
the deposit organs for all the relevant treaties on the issue
concerning the application of relevant multilateral international
treaties to the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) as
of July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the days to come, the Chinese government will also
comprehensively elaborate, through the Secretary General of the
UN, to the international community the principles and approaches
regarding the application of the relevant international treaties
to the HKSAR, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Through the above-mentioned actions, the overwhelming majority
of the multilateral international treaties currently applying to
Hong Kong will continue to be applicable to the HKSAR as of July
1, 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
These treaties are relating to economy and trade, customs,
science and technology, civil aviation, merchant ships,
intellectual property rights, resources, environmental protection,
postal service, human rights, labor, international crimes, private
international laws and other areas, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He added that altogether there are more than 200 such
individual treaties, over 80 of which China hasn't acceded to by
now.
</P>
<P>
The cations mentioned above are taken for the purpose of
implementing the "one country, two systems" principle as well as
the relevant provisions of the Basic Law of the HKSAR, he said,
adding that they are, therefore, of great significance to Hong
Kong's smooth transition and to the preservation of its long-term
prosperity and stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
