<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Region Improving Household Contract System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region has become China's largest cotton producer and a major
grain production base thanks to an improved household contract
responsibility system.
</P>
<P>
China adopted the system, which links profit to output, in the
early 1980s, and agricultural productivity was greatly raised as a
result. Xinjiang was one of the places that experienced these
changes. But this largest region in China, with more than 1.6
million sq km of land and vast amounts of farmland, has its own
farming methods distinct from other parts of China where parcels
of land are much smaller. So it added something to the system.
</P>
<P>
This included local governments being responsible for
efficiency, and farmers having the right to manage their own
farmland. Also important were five processes: unified production,
water conservation, mechanical operations, major technological
improvements, and various services.
</P>
<P>
"These five unified steps are meant to improve farm management
and are in line with the shift of economic growth from extensive
operations to intensive ones. And local officials are tied more
closely to farmland and field management," explains Zhang Zhennan,
research fellow of the regional Academy of Agricultural Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Officials are especially helpful in seeing that techniques are
applied or in providing information. Officials give on-the-spot
lectures on every aspect of the production chain. Banks in Hotan
county provided more than 16 million yuan of loans to cotton
growers in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang now produces more than a quarter of China's total
cotton output, and the improved system has played a major role in
this. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
