<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Moves to Save Watersheds: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines has taken a series
of measures to save the country's watershed areas which are in a
critical state due to unabated deforestation, a senior environment
official said today.
</P>
<P>
The unabated deforestation, which goes at an annual average of
130,000 hectares, is a main reason for the country's watershed
degradation, said Virgilio Marcelo, undersecretary for operations
at the Environment and Natural Resources Department.
</P>
<P>
In a report on the status of the country's watersheds, Marcelo
said watershed degradation is one of the causes of water shortage
experienced in parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Watershed degradation can also result in more serious problems
such as the increasing rate of soil erosion which can cause
landslides and flash floods, particularly during the southwest
monsoon period.
</P>
<P>
To abate the degradation of watershed areas, Marcelo said that
the environment department has taken a series of rehabilitation
and protection measures, including the establishment of forest
plantations, erosion control and environmental resources
enhancement.
</P>
<P>
For this year alone, the environment has targeted to establish
some 29,564 hectares of forest plantations and another 13,070
square meters of vegetation.
</P>
<P>
Marcelo also noted that the protection of some 132,460 hectares
of existing forests and 10 watershed areas is a priority for the
country.
</P>
<P>
Five more watersheds are scheduled to be declared as watershed
reservation this year to prevent inappropriate forest exploitation
and other disruptive land use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Leads to Expected Fall in Australia's Farm Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Australia's chief commodities
forecaster today downgraded its long-term commodity exports
forecast by 1.2 billion US dollars because of an expected five
percent drop in farm exports due to dry weather and the developing
El Nino.
</P>
<P>
But the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource
Economics (ABARE) increased its forecast for total commodity
exports in the 1996-97 financial year (from July 1, 1996 to June
30,1997) to 44.4 billion US dollars, up from an earlier prediction
of 44.2 billion US dollars and 2.6 percent higher than the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
In its June quarter commodities outlook, the bureau said total
commodity exports were expected to rise to a record 46.2 billion
US dollars in 1997-98, mainly due to 29 billion US dollars from
minerals and energy exports.
</P>
<P>
But the figure compared to earlier predictions of exports worth
47.4 billion US dollars in 1997-98, due mainly to a 3.35 billion
US dollar fall in the expected value of farm exports.
</P>
<P>
"Prospects of drier than normal seasonal conditions, as a
result of a developing El Nino weather pattern, will contribute to
a forecast five percent fall in the value of farm exports to 15.3
billion US dollars in 1997-98," ABARE acting executive director
Stephen Beare said.
</P>
<P>
ABARE said lower winter crop production and lower grain exports
were major factors in the forecast fall in farm exports.
</P>
<P>
Crop yields were expected to be below average in Australia's
eastern states, reflecting the Bureau of Meteorology's
announcement that it was confident an El Nino weather pattern will
persist for the remainder of the year.
</P>
<P>
El Nino suppresses winter rains in southern Australia and then
the monsoonal summer rains in the north. The full effects of El
Nino were last felt in Australia during the drought of 1982-83.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the value of wheat exports is forecast to plummet
40 percent in 1997-98 to 1.9 billion US dollars from record levels
this year of 3.19 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Wheat production is also seen falling from 23.586 million tons
this financial year to 16.245 million tons in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
But one bright spot on the horizon is wool, with the eastern
market indicator forecast to average six percent higher in 1997-98
at 494 US cents per kg clean, due to higher demand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment for China's Urban Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Great changes are taking
place in the cities of northern Hebei Province thanks to increased
overseas investment in urban construction in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The province has halted its practice of spending freely on
urban infrastructure, and has increased cooperation with overseas
investors instead. It used more than 14 million US dollars worth
of government donations or loans to build and upgrade public
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Sewage treatment plants in Handan and Shijiazhuang have begun
work, as has a gas project in the coastal city of
Qinhuangdao. Construction of 12 other projects is under way, for
water supplies, sewage disposal, and gasworks in major cities at a
total cost estimated at nearly 2.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
An urban water supply and environmental protection project,
involving a loan of 150 million US dollars, has been listed as
part of the 1997-1999 World Bank plan.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors have shown an interest in the province's
real estate market, and a total of 130 million US dollars has been
put into 115 joint ventures and another 100 projects have been
started in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Hebei has 34 cities and plans to urbanize 35 percent of its
area by the end of the century. This will require more than 10
billion yuan for urban infrastructure. So it has 70 key projects
that are open to overseas funding, for water supplies, sewage
treatment, garbage disposal, road improvements, and building
machinery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Collects 2.7 Billion Yuan for Railway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian province has
collected more than 2.7 billion yuan through various channels to
build two important railways.
</P>
<P>
The Zhangping-Quanzhou-Xiaochu railway line and another railway
from Nanping to Hengfeng in neighboring Jiangxi province (Hengnan
railway) need a total investment of nearly four billion yuan,
while the state has provided only 55 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
To ensure enough funds for the construction of the railways,
Fujian adopted different measures, such as using bank loans,
issuing credits and shares, attracting foreign investment, and
collecting funds from local units, the provincial authorities say.
</P>
<P>
At present, tracks on the Zhangquanxiao railway have been laid
to Shanyao station in Quanzhou, and that on the Hengnan railway,
to Wuyishan station. Part of the railways has gone into
operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
