<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Enjoy More Eminent Status beyond 1997: ROK Businessman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- "After Hong Kong returns to
China on July 1, not only my chamber and I myself will remain in
Hong Kong, my son and daughter will come to work here, too," Sung
Suk Joo, chairman of the Korean Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong
said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
One of the founders of the chamber, the 50-year-old Sung has
been in Hong Kong for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
"I love Hong Kong, especially its free trade and financial
systems, freedom of entrance and exit, and good investment
environment, which have brought easy accesses to business people
from the Republic of Korea (ROK) and other countries here," said
Sung at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The chamber now boasts more than 260 members as against the
merely 40-plus people when it was first established in 1976.
</P>
<P>
The trade between the ROK and Hong Kong is also developing
rapidly, with an average annual growth rate of 15 to 20 percent,"
Sung added.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the total trade volume between the ROK and Hong Kong
reached 12 billion US dollars, mainly from automobiles, chemical
and electronic products.
</P>
<P>
To help more people to acquaint themselves with the ROK and
expand new scope for the ROK-Hong Kong trade, Sung said, his
chamber has, through the local ATV, sponsored a special "Korean
Hour" program, and a 30-minute English new reports program a week
with Chinese subtitles.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are more than 800 ROK enterprises and some
7,000 ROK nationals residing in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that more businessmen from ROK and other countries
will come to Hong Kong after July 1, for ROK business people there
are more opportunities here than in their own country," Sung
claimed.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he added, he would ask both his son and daughter,
who are now studying at college in the ROK, to come to work in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"I am also thinking of sending them to Beijing first to learn
Putonghua (or Standard Chinese), because they will have more
chances to communicate with people from the Chinese interior area
after the return of Hong Kong," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Describing Hong Kong as a metropolis in the world playing the
role of international financing, trading and shipping center, Sung
predicted that Hong Kong will acquire an still more important
position after its return.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that "China's interior area is a huge market
with vast potential, and Hong Kong will play a crucial role in
supporting and promoting the modernization drive there."
</P>
<P>
The principle of "one country, two systems", which the Chinese
government is to implement in Hong Kong from July 1, is in the
interest of both Hong Kong and the Chinese interior area.
</P>
<P>
"As long as the full implementation of this principle is
guaranteed, the existing economic system in Hong Kong will remain
unchanged," Sung said, adding that it is not only good for Hong
Kong but beneficial to the Chinese interior area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
