<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Raid District Town in W. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Rebels raided and partially
overran Bundybugyo district town in western Uganda early Monday
and were soon repulsed by Uganda army, said a senior Ugandan
officer.
</P>
<P>
Jeje Odongo, State Minister for Defense in charge of training,
said the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) rebels launched the raid
along with soldiers from former Zaire and Rwandese Hutu militia
and occupied a part of the town.
</P>
<P>
According to Odong, between 100 and 200 rebels had taken part
in the attack. They acted in two groups: one manoeuvred outside
Congo-Uganda border to attract heavy deployment from Bundybugyo,
and the other raided the town where only a few soldiers and
policemen stationed.
</P>
<P>
However, the remaining unit in the town resisted, and when the
reinforcement arrived, the attackers escaped, Odongo said.
</P>
<P>
Five rebels were killed in the battle whereas casualty of
government troops is not available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
