<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Madagascar to Enhance Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Madagascar today
agreed to form a joint commission as soon as possible to further
enhance their bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a meeting here today between
Malaysian Acting Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim and Madagascar
Deputy Prime Minister Tantely Andrianarivo, Secretary-General of
the Finance Ministry Clifford Herbert told reporters after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The proposed joint commission would include cooperation in the
field of cultural and scientific development as well as technical
cooperation, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"The (Madagascar) Prime Minister is planning to come to
Malaysia in the later part of the year. So we are working on some
agreements to enable us to sign them during the visit," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar and Andrianarivo, both finance ministers of their
respective countries, also agreed to enhance trade relations
between the two countries which at present was very minimal.
</P>
<P>
"They are very keen to invite our businessmen to go there and
help develop tourism and other sectors. Our businessmen are also
going there and are looking for possibilities to explore business
there," Clifford Herbert added.
</P>
<P>
According to Director of the Malaysian External Trade
Development Corporation (MATRADE) Mohammed Abdul Halim, Malaysia's
trade with the republic showed a 15 percent decrease in exports at
20.24 million ringgit (about 8.1 million U.S. dollars) last year
from 23.89 million ringgit (about 9.56 million dollars ) in l995.
</P>
<P>
But, imports from Madagascar rose by 69 percent to 1.76 million
ringgit (about 700,000 million dollars) in l996 from l.04 million
ringgit (about 400,000 million dollars) in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's main exports to Madagascar include animal and
vegetable oils and fats, miscellaneous manufactured articles and
manufactured goods while its main imports from that country were
food and live animals, commodities, manufactured goods, machinery
and transport equipment.
</P>
<P>
The Madagascar deputy prime minister arrived here Monday for a
two-day visit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
