<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Farmers Become Townfolks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The dream of Chinese farmers of
becoming townfolks has come true almost overnight in east China's
Zhejiang Province, as local authorities offer farmers a permanent
residence card that carries with it urban residence status.
</P>
<P>
Chinese farmers have often had difficulties finding jobs in
cities because they don't have the necessary urban residence
cards. But many farmers expect their children to go to college or
find better work or become cadres of some kind and try to move to
urban areas to escape the limits there.
</P>
<P>
But, in a counter move, booming townships and villages became
more attractive to farmers after China's rural reforms began in
the early 1980s. This caused a growing number to remain in the
countryside and contribute to rural urbanization.
</P>
<P>
One example of this was farmers in 18 districts and 12 villages
of Zhejiang's Longgang Township who recently began to receive the
same treatment as city dwellers in schooling, employment,
insurance, family planning, and other rights.
</P>
<P>
Longgang was just a small fishing village in the early 1980s
when the county began to encourage farmers elsewhere to open up
wasteland there. So, the farmers poured in, and with their hard
work, set up an entirely new city on the beach.
</P>
<P>
Its population has grown to 140,000 and it has nearly four
billion yuan in industrial and agricultural output value
annually. Its 87 streets are crowded with businesses, factories,
and tall buildings.
</P>
<P>
Longgang was the first to benefit from China's effort to
promote urbanization in small townships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
