<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.African Official Stresses Need to Overcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 17 (Xinhua) --The South African Deputy
Agriculture Minister has stressed the need for South African
farmers to work with overseas partners to overcome the legacy of
a segregated agriculture system.
</P>
<P>
Addressing foreign envoys at a function here last week, South
African Deputy Agriculture Minsiter Thoko Didiza said that it was
necessary for the partners to understand what each other wanted
from such a relationship in agriculture, especially commercial
farming, local daily "Business" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Didiza said that to guarantee food security and close the gap
between rich and poor farmers, while creating a dynamic and
competitive sector that contributed to economy, interaction with
the international community would be mainly targeted in the areas
of technological transfer, agricultural research, training,
information and trade.
</P>
<P>
"From the South African perspective, we move from a premise
that in achieving our goals for transformation, we will require
various expertise, some of which we do not have as a country, but
some of your countries indeed offer," she said.
</P>
<P>
She also stressed that South Africa needed to locate its
economic growth within the parameters of the international trade
environment and see how they would benefit from South African
farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
