<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Maintain Good Relationship With Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Veena Sikri, Consul General of
India in Hong Kong, said Hong Kong's return to China is a
historical event.
</P>
<P>
"The event is also very important for us as we have a large
Indian community in Hong Kong," she said in a recent interview,
adding that the Indian community in Hong Kong has approximately
28,000 members and has existed here for more than a century.
</P>
<P>
Indians have been involved in every aspect of economic
activities in Hong Kong -- in trade, business and commerce. The
Indian community in Hong Kong leads a very happy life and looks
forward to continued prosperity here, she said.
</P>
<P>
India and Hong Kong have always maintained good relations,
according to Sikri. Hong Kong has been India's fourth largest
trading partner, and their bilateral trade reached almost three
billion US dollars in value last year, she said.
</P>
<P>
Sikri expressed satisfaction over Hong Kong's investment
environment as well as appreciation for what she called its
laissez-faire financial policies. Such policies, she said, have
promoted the development of Hong Kong as an international
financial center.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly hope that Hong Kong will continue to develop and
prosper in future," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I think all of us in Asia accept the 'one country, two
systems' formula. We look forward very much to the implementation
of this policy."
</P>
<P>
On consular matters, Sikri said, the Indian government has
decided to recognize the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
passport as a valid document from July 1. "We'll continue our
bonds and our relationship with Hong Kong after the handover," she
said.
</P>
<P>
India has also maintained very active and good relations with
China, she said, citing as proof Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
visit to India in November, 1996. "It was a good visit. There is a
good prospect for both sides. We look forward to continuing good
relations with China," she said.
</P>
<P>
Dipak Mallik, counselor of the Indian Consulate in Hong Kong,
said India's trade with Hong Kong grew by two percent to reach
2.711 billion US dollars in 1996, compared with 2.655 billion US
dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
A big number of Indian companies are doing business with many
countries from Hong Kong as it is a very important trade and
financial center in this part of the world and serves as a link to
America, Latin America, Europe and Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hong Kong's investment in India has increased
steadily in recent years, according to Mr. Mallik. With the
liberalization of the Indian economy since 1991, he said, there
has been greater scope for making profits in India. Investment has
kept flowing into India from all over the world, and Hong Kong has
been one of the major sources of such investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Indian nationals who are highly qualified in the
fields of technology, banking, finance and insurance have kept
coming to Hong Kong in large numbers, he said. The Indian
community is contributing to their own prosperity and to the
prosperity of Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
