<HEADLINE> S. Africa Joins in Constructing World's Third </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- South African construction
expertise is heavily involved in building one of the world's tallest
hotel in Dubai, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), local daily the Star
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The 321-meter high Chicago Beach Tower hotel -- built in the
shape of a ship's sail -- already dominates Dubai's spectacular
skyscraper horizon, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The building will be topped off by a 104-meter mast and includes
200 suites, an aquarium at ground-floor level, and swimming pools 150
meter above the ground. There is also a helicopter landing area and an
all-glass sky restaurant.
</P>
<P>
The construction will be the third largest in the world, being
bettered only by the new Hong Kong airport and the Petronas Towers in
Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The South African partners in the international joint venture
putting up the building are Murray and Roberts Construction
International Ltd.. Other partners are from UAE and Australia.
</P>
<P>
So far, the building has reached a height of 210 meters since the
construction started a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
