<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> I'm Proud to Be Member of HKSAR Govt, Says Gordon Siu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- "Hong Kong is my home and China
is my
motherland. I am proud to be a member of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) government, serving my home and my
motherland," said Secretary for Transport Gordon Siu Kwing-chue in
an inclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
As head of the Hong Kong Government's transport branch since
June 1996, Siu oversees the construction and management of the
road, railway and ferry systems in Hong Kong. He has been
appointed SAR's Secretary for Transport upon nomination of Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa.
</P>
<P>
The road system related to Hong Kong's new airport at Chek Lap
Kok, which is now under construction and due to be completed in
1998, plays an important role in the overall improvement of the
local transportation network.
</P>
<P>
"With the completion of this road system, we've begun an
overall study into Hong Kong's transport needs in the next
century," Siu said.
</P>
<P>
An outline focused on transport improvement for the period
2000-2015 with up-to-date technologies is to be ready by 1998, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has long been challenged by the world's busiest road
network, with more than 467,000 licensed vehicles traveling on
roads totaling just 1,743 kilometers in length.
</P>
<P>
Among the major projects to be considered are the so-called
Western and Eastern Corridors, passageways located in the eastern
and western parts of Kowloon, and bridges which link Hong Kong and
South China's Shenzhen and Zhuhai. The two cities are in the
Zhujiang River Delta, which represents one of China's most
vigorous economies.
</P>
<P>
The Delta area, which has witnessed rapid economic progress
during
the past decade, has established close ties with Hong Kong. Even
closer cooperation is foreseen after Hong Kong's handover, Siu
said.
</P>
<P>
It poses a big challenge for Hong Kong to improve interport
transportation with the area, which is predicted to witness a
considerably increased volume of transport in the years to come,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Railway and Mass Transit Railway (MTR) network is also to be
extended. After the West Rail passenger railway project is
completed around 2002-2003, large areas of land would become
available for development.
</P>
<P>
And the MTR line along the northern coast of Hong Kong Island
is planned to be extended eastward to cover almost the whole of
the coast line, he said.
</P>
<P>
To make better use of Hong Kong's waterways is also important.
With marine and river transportation reaching almost all ports in
Guangdong Province, Hong Kong will continue to benefit from
chances offered by the waterways, Siu predicted.
</P>
<P>
With about 10 different projects on the blue print for the next
10 to 15 years though, Siu is not worried about implementation.
"I'm very optimistic. Just look how we did for the New Airport
Core Program and related projects during the past five years. It
has most clearly demonstrated Hong Kong's capability in
infrastructure projects," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And we can do it even better since we've learnt a lot and we
can apply the experience gained," he said.
</P>
<P>
Born in Hong Kong in November 1945, Siu got a Master's Degree
in Public Administration from the University of Birmingham,
Britain, in 1975. He joined the government in February 1966, as
an Executive Officer. He joined the Hong Kong Administration
Service in 1968.
</P>
<P>
He later took up such posts as Postmaster General, Commissioner
for Transport and Secretary for Economic Services before being
appointed Secretary for Transport in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Divorced, Siu has two sons.
</P>
<P>
Siu gets up early, goes out for a walk and does golf swings in
the morning air. "This makes me feel fresh and energetic the
whole day," he said.
</P>
<P>
With wide-ranging hobbies including reading, golf and swimming,
his top spare time favorite is music -- classics, jazz, pop to
rock and roll Chinese and Western. He plays the violin, the
viola, the double bass and the guitar.
</P>
<P>
"Music is for one's soul," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
