<HEADLINE> Irani, Pakistani Leaders Share Views on Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Irani and Pakistani leaders have
shared the view that it is not war but peace talks that will solve
the ongoing crisis in Afghanistan, the Iran's official IRNA news
agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
This view was expressed at a meeting here last night between
Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani and the visiting
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Islamabad and Tehran are at odds on their supports for rival
Afghan factions. Iran accuses Pakistan of supporting the Islamic
militia Taliban which has already controlled 90 percent of the
territory in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"The only basic way and a permanent solution to the ongoing
crisis is the participation of all factions (in peace talks) based
on the interests of the Afghan people who have suffered through
the crisis," Rafsanjani said during the talks.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani termed as positive the role of Iran, Pakistan and
other regional countries in efforts to resolve the crisis in
Afghanistan and the crises elsewhere in the region.
</P>
<P>
Sharif arrived here yesterday afternoon. This is the first
visit by Sharif since becoming prime minister last February.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Sharif said that Pakistan is always holding
the opinion that military solution can not be successful in any one
of the regional crisis.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders expressed their satisfaction over progress towards
broadening of ties between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani called for further promotion of bilateral relations
particularly in the economic, trade and cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by IRNA, Iran and Pakistan reached an
agreement on defining of the two countries' marine borders in the
Gulf of Oman.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which was signed in the presence of Rafsanjani
and Sharif, is the first ever document to be signed between
Iran and its neighborly countries on defining the territorial
waters.
</P>
<P>
The accord is designed to safeguard the marine interests of
the two neighboring countries and is expected to play a
significant role in the exploitation of regional sea resources
in addition to promotion of cooperation and regional solidarity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
