<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Not Ready to Excavate Qin Shihuang's Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists say that they
will not excavate the tomb of Qin Shihuang, the first man to unite
China 2,000 years ago, in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Lack of advanced scientific means may bring problems to the
protection of relics during excavation, said Zhang Wenbin,
director of the State Cultural Relics Bureau, adding that the
bureau's current focus is to rescue those relics which are being
threatened by on-going construction projects.
</P>
<P>
But Qin Shihuang's tomb, 30 kilometers away from Xi'an, capital
of northwest China's Shaanxi province, is not on the emergency
list, he said. "It is impossible for us to dig any ancient
emperor's tomb without large amounts of funding, materials and
human resources."
</P>
<P>
The Qin Dynasty (221-206 BC) existed only for five
years. However, construction of the tomb started when the emperor
was only a 13-year-old boy. More than 800,000 workers spent dozens
of years completing the project, probably the biggest mausoleum in
the world.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists from both at home and abroad are very interested
in the things that may be in the tomb.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Zhongyi, head of a team to study terrecotta figures, said
that many technological problems have not yet been solved related
to the excavation of the tomb.
</P>
<P>
"To excavate the tomb, we must first remove the artificial
hilltop, a historical landmark, built on the tomb. It will be a
big job, and that would mean the destruction of the hilltop which
itself is of importance," he told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He also discussed the underground flow beneath the tomb. It is
not easy to pump the water out without damaging the tomb, he said.
</P>
<P>
Another problem is the treatment of a huge mercury layer in the
tomb.
</P>
<P>
In addition, iron and wooden materials buried with the emperor,
as well as silk and cloth fabrics, can not be well preserved if
they are exposed in the air. How to protect them is still a
technological problem, Yuan added.
</P>
<P>
"But someday we will be able to uncover the myth of the tomb in
line with the advancement of science and technology," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa to Set up National Youth Organization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The South African Youth
Council (SAYC), the first co-ordinating body of its kind to deal
with youth matters in civil society, will be set up on August 2,
a local daily The Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by the National Economic Development and
Labour Council (NEDLAC) in Cape Town, about 40 youth
organisations nationwide agreed on the establishment of SAYC.
</P>
<P>
NEDLAC was approached by the youth movements of the African
National Congress, National Party and Inkatha Freedom Party to
spearhead moves to form a national youth body and it convened two
meetings in April and June to facilitate the process, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The proposed August launch signaled an important coming
together of youth organisations in order to play a more active
role in broader civil society, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The SAYC will also ensure that youth issues are catered for
in forums such as NEDLAC and the Non-Governmental Organisation
Coalition.
</P>
<P>
It aims to assist in the integration of youth in all
government programs and policies through organs such as the
statutory National Youth Commission.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, South African youths held a series of gatherings
throughout the country to mark Youth Day and commemorate the 21st
anniversary of the Soweto student uprising of June 16, 1976 to
protest the forced use of Afrikaans as a medium of instruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
