<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia to Tap Mineral Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, June 17 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region is trying to turn its resources into an economic
advantage by following China's strategy of shifting energy and
resource development westward to speed up economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The region's mineral resources are estimated to be worth 13
trillion yuan. But the lack of technology has limited its
exploration of the resources, says Wang Jie, an official with the
regional Department of Geology and Mineral Resources.
</P>
<P>
The region has 133 of China's 165 types of minerals, 30 of
which rank among the largest reserves in the country.
</P>
<P>
Its coal reserves are said to be more than 200 billion
tons. They lie in the valleys of the Yellow and other rivers
which provide abundant water for generating electricity. But the
current annual mining capacity is less than 50 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In the Horqin, Erenhot, and Ordos oilfields, 140 million tons
of available oil and 30 billion cubic meters of natural gas have
been found.
</P>
<P>
The region also leads the world in proven rare-earths reserves
which are estimated at 100 million tons, and its reserves of
nonferrous metals amount to 30 million tons, while iron ore
reserves are as much as two billion tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
