<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Minister on Cooperation with HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In recent years, an increasing number of Hong Kong students
have come to study in universities in inland areas and, after
graduation, they have contributed to the development of Hong Kong,
Zhu said. He noted that at present more than 1,000 Hong Kong
students are studying some 30 majors in more than 100 universities
in the interior.
</P>
<P>
Universities in inland areas will take necessary steps to
make it more convenient for Hong Kong students in entrance exams,
tuition, and in their daily lives, he pledged. "After Hong Kong's
return, universities in inland areas will, as always, welcome Hong
Kong students to enroll in these universities."
</P>
<P>
When asked whether middle school students from inland areas
will be permitted to enroll in universities in Hong Kong, Zhu
pointed out that this issue will be decided by the SEC and the
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region through
discussions.
</P>
<P>
As for entrance exams, the number of admissions, and the amount
of tuition, these must be negotiated by the two sides in
accordance with their particular situations, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Mutual recognition of academic scores and degrees by
universities in inland areas and Hong Kong must be taken into
account when they are decided by the central educational department
and its Hong Kong counterpart through negotiations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that the nine-year free education system was
implemented in Hong Kong very early and Hong Kong's achievements
in primary and middle school education, vocational training, and
higher education are worth studying by inland areas.
</P>
<P>
He said it takes ten years to grow a tree, and a hundred to
raise a person. In similar fashion, cooperation in education
between inland areas and Hong Kong will be a long-term project and
will contribute to both the enduring prosperity and stability of
Hong Kong, and to the educational and scientific development of
inland areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
