<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Prime Minister Spends Holiday In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Mrs. Sirimavo R. D. Bandaranaike,
Prime Minister of Sri Lanka, spent her holiday in China from May
30 to June 15 at the invitation of the Chinese government, and
used the visit to have a talk with Chinese Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China and Sri Lanka are close friends and that
bilateral relations have always been good, and that there are no
problems between the two countries that have not been solved.
</P>
<P>
It is the Chinese government's established policy and the
common aspiration of the two peoples that a good-neighborly and
cooperative relationship to the mutual benefit be developed
between the two countries on the basis of the Five Principles of
Peaceful Co-existence, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that Sino-Sri Lankan ties will see even
bigger progress by the turn of the century with joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Bandaranaike expressed her thanks for the warm reception
provided by the Chinese government. Sri Lankan-Chinese links have
grown smoothly in recent years and the constructive projects
assisted by China are welcome in Sri Lanka, she told Li.
</P>
<P>
She said that these projects have had a positive impact on
politics, the economy, and social development in Sri Lanka, and
that she believes that the friendship between her country and
China will be enhanced in the future.
</P>
<P>
Chen Muhua, vice-chairwoman of the Standing Committee of the
Chinese National People's Congress, also met with
Mrs. Bandaranaike. 
</P>
