<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Trade Deficit Drops Drastically </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' trade deficit
dropped by 34.8 percent to 860 million U.S. dollars in April from
1.3 billion dollars for the same period last year, the National
Statistics Office said today.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the year-ago figures, the country's imports grew
by 4.7 percent to 2.9 billion dollars, while its exports rose by
39.5 percent to 2.1 billion dollars, according to figures released
by the office.
</P>
<P>
For the first four months, the country's trade deficit settled
at 3.8 billion dollars, a 5.9-percent decline from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Also year-on-year, the Philippines' imports for the period
increased 11.6 percent to 11.3 billion dollars, while its exports
went up 22.8 percent to 7.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
During the period, Japan was the country's largest trading
partner with their total trade reaching 24.4 billion dollars. It
was followed by the United States, South Korea and Singapore.
</P>
</TEXT>
