<HEADLINE> Israel's Labor Party Wants to Learn Blair's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The new leader of Israel's
opposition Labor Party is considering everything from learning
secret of election success of Western politicians to renaming his
party's name -- with an aim to topple the current government.
</P>
<P>
Ehud Barak is planning to learn the secret of British Prime
Minister Tony Blair's stunning success in elections on May 1, the
Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
A team of experts will be sent to London to find out how Blair
rehabilitated the British Labor Party and brought it back to power.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to make use of his experience and to employ his
methods here," Barak was quoted Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Barak, a former army Chief of Staff, said he did not
rule out the possibility of renaming his party as Blair did
with his party. He is seriously considering changing the name
to "the New Labor Party."
</P>
<P>
"This may have a psychological significance, though I am
aware that a name isn't everything and that the really
important thing is the substance of the message. But even
names and appearances have their importance," Barak said.
</P>
<P>
Barak's suggestion of renaming the party has aroused both
positive and negative reactions from within the Party.
</P>
<P>
Barak scored a convincing victory in the party leadership
election held on June 3 by winning 50 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Barak, 55, is widely regarded as a heavyweight challenger
to the current Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu of the Likud
Party. Barak has openly declared his goal of toppling the
Netanyahu government to replace it.
</P>
<P>
Despite his endorsement of the peace process with the Arabs,
Barak is a hawk in the leftist camp who stresses the importance of
preserving Israel's security in any peace deals. So he is dubbed
as "Mr. Security" like the slain premier Yithzak Rabin, whose
political legacy of striving to reach peace in the Middle East
Barak has been vowed to carry on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
