<HEADLINE> Rockwell to Expand R&AMP;D Centers in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Rockwell Semiconductor Systems,
the world's leading modem manufacturer, expects to increase the
number of employees at its Israel-based centers from next year,
today's Jerusalem Post reported.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Rockwell Semiconductor Systems, a subsidiary of
industrial automation giant Rockwell International Corp.,
announced the establishment of a research and development center
in Herzliya near Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The company already had a center in Karmiel in northern
Israel which it acquired from the US-based Comstream.
</P>
<P>
"We came here because of the people and talent and because we
felt we could build a strong product development team," company
president Dwight Decker said.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the number of employees will raise Rockwell's
local investment from 10 million U.S. dollars to 15 million
dollars per year, Decker said.
</P>
<P>
The decision to set up a local R&AMP;D center is part of the
company's transition from an aerospace and defense company to a
high-tech commercial electronics firm, he added.
</P>
<P>
The center in Herzliya will design software-based modems,
which are more flexible and less expensive than the currently
used hardware modems, and the Karmiel center is engaged in
developing satellite modems.
</P>
<P>
Decker revealed that Rockwell Semiconductor Systems' revenues
totalled 1.5 billion dollars last year, representing some 20
percent of Rockwell International's 8 billion dollars in
annual sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
