<HEADLINE> Sylvite Deposit Discovered in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Geological prospecting showed that
63 million tons of sylvite reserves have been discovered in Lop
Nur, a lake dried up in a desolate area in northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Sylvite is badly needed in China for making potash fertilizer,
which is of great importance for crop cultivation.
</P>
<P>
China needs annually three million tons of potash fertilizer
and about 2.7 million tons are imported from other countries.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, such rare minerals as saltpetre, chile nitre
and potash saltpetre have been discovered in Lop Nur as well.
</P>
<P>
Geological survey indicates that the lake basin is possibly an
area rich in oil and gas reserves and exploitation will be
launched in the area in the later half of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
