<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Hosts Meeting to Assist Poor Micro-Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- About 130 representatives of donors
and multilateral institutions gathered here today at the Asian
Development Bank headquarters to explore ways of providing more
financial services to poor micro-enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the fourth meeting of the Consultative Group to
Assist the Poorest (CGAP) that will last three days, ADB President
Mitsuo Sato introduced the bank's efforts in providing financial
support to these enterprises and lessons from the operations.
</P>
<P>
"ADB's leading mix is consciously oriented to balance economic
growth objectives with projects that provide direct support for
human development, reduction of poverty, improvement of the role
of women and environmental protection," he added.
</P>
<P>
Financial services to poor micro-enterprises may be the single
most effective way to alleviate poverty and achieve broad-based
economic growth in the Asian Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
In developing countries, the micro-enterprise sector employs 30
to 80 percent of the economically active population and often
absorbs excess labor during periods of economic restructuring,
according to a document released by the CGAP Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
However, it was estimated that only fewer than two percent of
the five million people running micro-enterprises have access to
financial services in the region, where more than two thirds of
the poor people in the developing world are living and about one
billion of them are considered to live in absolute poverty.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1995, the CGAP has now 23 member donors with a fund
of 200 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Also attending today's meeting is the World Bank's vice
president Ismail Serageldin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Study Gimmick of Transfer Pricing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Finance Ministry said today
it will probe a tax swindle which involves India-based
multinational companies (MNCs) with respect to dealings with their
international affiliates.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the ministry said MNCs are using transfer pricing
to understate their tax liability.
</P>
<P>
The system of transfer pricing determines the price at which
products or technology are sold between group companies.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry believes that with steep cuts in import
tariffs since 1991, several MNCs have started to source their
imports from foreign group companies, and similarly, domestic
units are engaging in exports to either the parent outfit or
affiliate companies.
</P>
<P>
At present, there is no database in the country on the transfer
pricing practice adopted by the MNCs vis-a-vis their affiliates.
</P>
<P>
"They are not charitable organizations. In countries like
America they know how these MNCs function, that is distribute
their prices between branches and subsidiaries across the world
and what part of it is in their country and what is remitted. So
we have major gaps in the area," a Finance Ministry source said.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the Finance Ministry has asked the National
Institute of Public Finance and Policy to undertake a study on
transfer pricing and the arms length practice adopted by MNCs
operating in India.
</P>
<P>
India's Revenue Department had earlier ordered a crackdown on
the practice of payment adopted by MNCs with regard to the
emoluments of their employees. It found that in several cases part
of the wage bill was paid by the company in their parent country
because the income tax rates there were much lower.
</P>
<P>
It is feared that MNCs tend to underinvoice their exports from
India and overvalue the imports from their foreign affiliates
located in countries with low tax regimes. By transferring goods
back to India (through imports) at a higher price, the incidence
of tax on the domestic entity is considerably lowered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
