<HEADLINE> Education Minister on Cooperation With Hong Kong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Zhu Kaixuan, the minister in
charge of China's State Education Commission (SEC), said that it
will not interfere in Hong Kong's educational affairs, nor will it
establish any institution in the region.
</P>
<P>
He added in an interview with Xinhua: "The State Education
Commission and its Hong Kong counterpart will not be subordinate
to each other, according to the stipulations of the Basic Law and
the central government."
</P>
<P>
However, this does not mean that there will be no connection
between the two, he added, expressing confidence in the future of
their cooperation. He said that after the return of Hong Kong,
both sides will most certainly increase cooperation and supply
more talented people for the country.
</P>
<P>
He said cooperation between educational groups from both sides
has grown rapidly in recent years, and schools at different levels
have had many exchange programs involving mutual visits, study
tours, seminars, and summer camps.
</P>
<P>
Patriots from various walks of life in Hong Kong have been
especially helpful in the educational development of inland areas
for years, donating money, building schools, and setting up funds,
he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Schools and institutions under the State Education Commission
organized trips involving 2,500 people to Hong Kong in 1996, while
more than 2,000 people from Hong Kong visited inland areas, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
