<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Import Refined Petroleum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Petroleum
Enterprise announced Monday that Ethiopia was making preparations
for importing refined petroleum as the Assab Oil Refinery will
stop operation starting from August 1 of this year.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Yigzaw Mekennen, general manager
of the enterprise following an agreement reached between Ethiopia
and Eritrea with regard to the cost effectiveness of importing
petroleum rather than using the refinery.
</P>
<P>
A local report said, the cost for petroleum refining at the
Assab Oil Refinery has been rising each year whereas that of the
imported oil was declining. The cost for a metric ton of refined
petroleum at Assab in the first quarter of the year was 520 Birr
(about 57 U.S. Dollars), much higher than that of the same amount
of imported oil.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has already begun importing oil via Djibouti.
</P>
