<HEADLINE> China Prepares Against Yellow River Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- China is putting the final
touches on flood-prevention efforts on the Yellow River, the
country's second largest, which has been lying tamed for about 50
years.
</P>
<P>
But the river bed has continued to rise, increasing the
potential for flooding.
</P>
<P>
China has repaired 223 water conservation facilities that were
damaged during last year's flood season. The country has gathered
a supply of rocks, wires, gunny sacks, and rubber boats along the
banks, according to an official from the Yellow River Anti-Flood
and Drought-Control Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Henan and Shandong provinces, which lie along the lower reaches
of the river, have also mobilized more than one million farmers
trained to fight floods, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
