<HEADLINE> East China Intensifies Pollution Control Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- East China's Xiamen has ordered a
number of heavily polluting factories to stop production as part
of its efforts to make the city a model in environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
The factories are mainly situated near the city's two big water
sources. Eight of them have been fined and 31 asked to improve
within a prescribed time limit.
</P>
<P>
Industrial pollution is one of the major reasons for a
deteriorating urban environment, but pollution controls have meant
that the city's environmental quality has been kept at the level
of the 1980s while it enjoys rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The city has since the beginning of this year intensified its
efforts to fight pollution. It has closed 28 factories with
serious pollution problems last year, and the result of follow-up
study showed that nearly 86 percent of them are operating better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Chinese City Has Lofty Commercial Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has given
Zhengzhou, the capital of Henan Province, approval to become a
national commercial and trade center.
</P>
<P>
A pilot plan won the approval of the State Commission for
Restructuring the Economy, the State Planning Commission, the
State Economic and Trade Commission, the Ministry of Internal
Trade, and the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales in Zhengzhou grew at an annual rate of more than
30 percent from 1990 to 1996, with that in 1996 reaching 21.6
billion yuan. The city has become a consumer goods center for the
central part of the country.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 large wholesale markets for building materials,
farm machinery, and other goods have been built in the city, and
its Commodities Exchange, which ranks first in China, handles more
than a fifth of the total volume of this kind of trade in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities say they will widen the market's scale, speed
up construction of farm produce markets, and improve
transportation, telecommunications, and other basic urban
facilities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
