<HEADLINE> Myanmar Minister on Future of State Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is working assiduously
towards enhanced privatization and liberalization of state-owned
enterprises and corporations, said a senior Myanmar official
today.
</P>
<P>
Brig. Gen. Abel, minister for National Planning and Economic
Development, said at the opening of a Myanmar Building Material
Expo'97 here that the future of state firms will be under four
scenarios -- total privatization, formation of companies, joint
ventures and public listed companies.
</P>
<P>
A stock exchange will be in place within the next two years
with a capital market already developing, he said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's annual GDP growth for the last eight years has been
an average of 7.5 per cent, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the construction industry, he predicted unprecedented growth
of 24.5 per cent, thanks to massive development projects in ports,
airports, industrial parks, hotels, highways, railways and
irrigation systems.
</P>
<P>
On the oil and gas industry, he disclosed that a pipeline from
Myanmar's Yadana gas field to Thailand is being built in
association with the French company of TOTAL and UNOCAL of the
U.S. The gas field is expected to be put into production by next
mid-year.
</P>
<P>
The hotel and tourist industry, mining, agriculture and
fisheries, telecommunications and power sectors are also showing
great promise, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
