<HEADLINE> India's Two Major Parties Identify President Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- India's two major political
parties, the ruling 15-party United Front and the Congress party,
have agreed to elevate present vice-president Kocheril Raman
Narayanan to the 11th president of the country.
</P>
<P>
The tenure of President Shankar Dayal Sharma expires at the end
of next month and the 11th presidential elections will be held on
July 14.
</P>
<P>
The United Front and Congress reached agreement on the new
president candidate after holding their core group meetings on
Monday. The election of Narayanan, a lower caste, to the top post
is almost a certainty now with both parties controlling nearly 60
percent of votes in the electoral college, which consists of the
elected members of parliament and the state assemblies in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the country's biggest
opposition, has also shown its willingness to support Narayanan as
the country's new president. BJP Secretary S.P. Gautam said on
Monday that his party would happily endorse the candidature of
Narayanan for the July 14 election to the post of president.
</P>
</TEXT>
