<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Return Good to Sino-British Ties: Legislator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Tom McNally, a member of the
British House of Lords (the upper house), today urged the British
people to be more positive and see the return of Hong Kong to its
motherland as an opportunity to widen the range of contacts
between Britain and China.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Baron McNally said the return of
Hong Kong should and could be used as an opportunity to develop
new and deeper relations with China.
</P>
<P>
McNally warned that the next few weeks before July 1, when
China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong, were
delicate and sensitive for the British and Chinese relations. The
issue should be handled carefully as some British people were
nostalgic and backward looking.
</P>
<P>
"I think what we've got to make sure of is that the way issues
are raised in the country, particularly in the next few weeks, is
in a positive way.
</P>
<P>
"In the long term, I don't think the problem exists, because
in the longer term, it is so obviously in Britain's interest to
build good relations with China."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will still be important in those contacts (between
the two countries) and still be an important point of entry for
anybody who wishes to enter China" for business, said McNally, who
served as political adviser to the Labor prime minister in 1976-79
(James Callaghan).
</P>
<P>
He admitted that because of Britain's Hong Kong
responsibilities, Britain had not been able to take a "broader"
look at relations with China. "Hong Kong, in a way, has been
distortion of our link with China."
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that disputes arose sometimes between Britain
and China on the Hong Kong issue, he was confident Hong Kong's
future would be bright because it would still retain the advantage
of being the most attractive gateway to China for many Western
countries and many Western enterprises.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to China on July 1, "we will have the
advantage of being integrated into a wider Chinese market and
society," McNally added.
</P>
<P>
Talking about some negative reports over Hong Kong's return in
British newspapers recently, McNally said it was easy to make
noises about Hong Kong and to play anti-Chinese sentiment in some
of British media. "But it doesn't do anything for the people of
Hong Kong; it doesn't do anything for the broader relations with
China which are in the interests of both Britain and China."
</P>
<P>
"I do think there are those in government, in parliament, and
in business who will be looking for a new approach to relations
with China and I am optimistic those are the views that will
prevail."
</P>
<P>
Regarding the future policies of Britain's new Labor
government, he said Labor came to office very close to the
transfer of power, and it could not change anything in the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Joint Declaration on the Question of Hong
Kong, signed by the British Conservative government and China on
December 19, 1984, he said:"My view is that Labor wants to honor
the agreement."
</P>
<P>
McNally said the Labor government will be sensitive to opinion
back home, but "I don't think it will want to damage the long-term
and broad relations with China. I think in the contrary, Labor
wants good and positive relations."
</P>
<P>
He added that Prime Minister Tony Blair and Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook had all indicated that policy clearly. "They wish to
establish, very quickly, very positive and business-like links
with China at both political and business levels."
</P>
<P>
On future relations between the two countries, McNally said
there were no major obstacles on the road to better ties. He hoped
what happened next after the hand-over would be a positive impetus
to boost ties with China and increase trade and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"I would hope there will be, at a reasonable time after the
hand-over, some high-level visits, and there will be real efforts
to identify areas of opportunities for increasing trade and
cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
McNally dubbed as unnecessary fears that China would not keep
its commitments and would meddle in Hong Kong's administrative
affairs.
</P>
<P>
"My view is that China has an excellent record of honoring its
international obligations, and I see no reason why that shouldn't
be the case for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said China's dynamic and fast-growing economy had offered a
wide range of possibilities for Britain, including cooperation in
the fields of culture, tourism, science and technology.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the return of Hong Kong to China will usher in a new
era for British-Chinese relations," he said confidently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
