<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Magurchhara Gasfield Still Burning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The gas-ignited devastating fire is
still out of control but the height of flame showed some reduction
for the third day today in Magurchhara Gasfield in northeastern
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Two fire fighting teams from Singapore and the United States
are expected today to begin their fighting against the biggest
gasfield fire, which erupted early Sunday following a massive
explosion in a gas well in the gasfield being operated by
Occidental of Bangladesh Ltd, a United States Company.
</P>
<P>
Witness said that the heat of the fire can be felt from a
distance of one kilometer and at night, the flames illuminate an
area of at least five kilometers. The flame is even visible from
Moulvibazar town, 26 kms away from the gasfield.
</P>
<P>
Energy Minister Noor Uddin Khan, who visited the gasfield
Monday morning, told the parliament that the massive fire has
caused no loss of life though it has damaged half a kilometer rail
track and the drilling rig and other accessories of the drilling
company.
</P>
<P>
The extent of damage was limited to a rig, few other drilling
equipment and the investment made by the Occidental for the
drilling, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The fire would not affect the reserve of the field, estimated
at about half a trillion cubic feet, he added.
</P>
<P>
A high-level inquiry committee, comprising representatives from
local administration and Occidental, has been formed to
investigate the cause of the devastating fire.
</P>
<P>
Some engineers said the fire broke out as gas was found at a
very early stage of drilling while they thought it would take very
deep digging.
</P>
<P>
There were two explosions of such type in Sylhet in the 1950s
and in Chittagong in the 1960s respectively, but the fires caused
by these blasts were not as big as the present one.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
