<HEADLINE> Former Sri Lankan Minister Detained under Security Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Former minister of the previous
United National Party (UNP) regime of Sri Lanka Sirisena Cooray
was detained Monday on the orders of Defense Secretary Chandananda
de Silva, according to police sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said he is being held in a government building in
Colombo on Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Cooray is also the head of a recently established controversial
R. Premadasa (former President of Sri Lanka) Center which has
planned major ceremonies in Colombo on June 29, the birth
anniversary of late president Premadasa who were assassinated on
May 1, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Asked why he was detained, the sources said the action is taken
under the Public Security Act.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the government is most likely to ban the
ceremony for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Four days ago, Colombo police ordered Cooray to surrender a
personal weapon issued to him about 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Since May this year, he has been organizing the Premadasa
Center and prepared for the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Cooray was minister of housing and local government and
 confidant of assassinated president Ranasinghe Premadasa of the
 UNP.
</P>
<P>
 The UNP's 17 year reign ended in 1994 when the ruling
 People's Alliance won presidential and general elections.
</P>
<P>
 Cooray returned to the island country in April after a
lengthy stay
 abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
