<HEADLINE> Scientists Urged To Dig Into Grassroots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Scientists are being urged to
pitch in at the grassroots level with practical help for the rural
poor.
</P>
<P>
Scientific research centers across China are to step up the
dissemination of up-to-date farming techniques in poverty-stricken
areas, focusing on skills necessary to improve the planting,
breeding and processing of agricultural and animal products --
down-to-earth work.
</P>
<P>
And regional scientific centers are to send experts to poor
areas to conduct in-depth research on local natural resources and
work out regional scientific development plans and upgrade pillar
industries.
</P>
<P>
The country's scientists were called on to do more to help the
nation's poverty-alleviation program in a document released Monday
by the State Science and Technology Commission (SSTC), the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS) and the Chinese Association for Science
and Technology (CAST).
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to technologies for increasing the
production of grain, cotton, edible oil, animal husbandry, aquatic
products and forestry, the document detailed.
</P>
<P>
Based on local natural resources, impoverished areas have
developed industries over the past few years which have helped
many farmers rise above the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
But product-quality is relatively poor because of outdated
technologies.
</P>
<P>
An average of 6,000 scientific research findings have been made
annually during the past few years. Only a few are applicable to
areas with harsh eco-systems and difficult geographic
environments, said Zhang Jingan, an official at the Technology
Development Center for Rural Areas under the SSTC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government' Fiscal Surplus Decreases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government posted a
fiscal surplus of 4.9 billion pesos (187 million U.S. dollars)
during the first five months this year, a 61-percent decline from
the year-ago level, the local newspaper Business World said today.
</P>
<P>
Citing a government report on the national cash budget
performance, the paper said the level was also
lower-than-expected.
</P>
<P>
The government, which recorded a surplus of 12.6 billion pesos
(481 million dollars) for the same period last year, had expected
a surplus of 11.3 billion pesos (431 million dollars) for the
first five months this year.
</P>
<P>
For the entire year, the government has targeted a surplus of
13 billion pesos (496 million dollars) with revenues projected at
483 billion pesos (18.4 billion dollars) and expenditures at 470
billion pesos (17.9 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The paper said the drop in the fiscal surplus was a result of
decreased revenues registered by the Bureau of Internal Revenue
and the Bureau of Customs during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
