<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photo Exhibition on Hong Kong Opens in Brussels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A photo exhibition entitled Hong
Kong's History and Its Evolution opened here today, a couple of
weeks before China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over the
region on July 1 to end Britain's 150-year colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, co-organized by the Chinese Embassy with the
Belgian Kingdom and the Belgium-China Cultural center, is composed
of four parts -- Hong Kong's history, its ties with the inland
areas, the process of transfer of power and today's Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 dignitaries attended the opening ceremony, at
which the Chinese Ambassador to the Belgian Kingdom, Song
Mingjiang, and Vice-President of the Belgium-China Cultural center
Bernard Dewit delivered speeches.
</P>
<P>
Song said the Chinese government could not only guarantee a
peaceful and smooth transfer of power over Hong Kong but also
could ensure the territory's long-term stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The peaceful resolution of the Hong Kong issue had set a new
example for resolving international disputes of the same nature,
particularly issues which had been left over historically between
countries.
</P>
<P>
Dewit said he was convinced the Chinese government would
respect the Fundamental Law, which stipulated that the Special
Administrative Region of Hong Kong would enjoy an elevated degree
of autonomy and that both its systems and living style would
remain unchanged over the next 50 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
