<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica To Defend Its Banana Quotas With EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica will defend the banana
quota it negotiated with the European Union (EU) through the
framework agreement signed on March 28, 1994, foreign trade
authorities said here today.
</P>
<P>
In the banana agreement signed among the EU and Costa Rica,
Colombia, Venezuela and Nicaragua, the EU granted Costa Rican
banana growers 23.4 percent of Latin American imports, according
to local press report today.
</P>
<P>
On September 27, 1995, the United States, Mexico, Honduras and
Guatemala denounced the EU'S fruit import system as discriminatory
before the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
To defend this Central American country's quota, Foreign Trade
Minister Jose Manuel Salazar will visit European countries this
coming July.
</P>
<P>
Salazar said that Costa Rica is permanently in movement to
defend the framework agreement it signed with the EU.
</P>
<P>
For this year at least, there will be no changes in the banana
trade with Europe.
</P>
<P>
Bananas are Costa Rica's principal export product and the
second largest generator of hard currency after tourism. In
1996 revenues from overseas banana sales totaled 611.4 million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
