<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wildlife Breeding in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province
has built more than 700 wildlife breeding farms and centers in
addition to its 24 natural reserves in order to better protect its
wildlife resources, biodiversity and natural ecology.
</P>
<P>
The farms are breeding a dozen species of animals listed for
priority protection by the state and the province, including such
rare and endangered species as giant salamanders and swans.
</P>
<P>
The province started building the farms in 1992. Up to the
present it has invested more than 30 million yuan (3.7 million US
dollars). The farms and centers now employ more than 2,500 people.
</P>
<P>
The provincial wildlife breeding farms and centers have
successfully bred more than 200 wild animals in some 30 species
listed for priority protection by the state.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the farms have succeeded in breeding more than
8,000 other animals of great commercial value. One ostrich farm in
Yongzhou city, which is financed by a businessman from Taiwan, has
invested more than two million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
