<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Consider Apology for Slavery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
says he will consider extending a national apology to black
Americans for slavery, but not compensation for their ancestors'
suffering.
</P>
<P>
"It's been so long and we're so many generations removed," he
says in a radio interview aired Monday.
</P>
<P>
The idea of an apology came from a white Ohio lawmaker who
introduced apology legislation in Congress last week.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the apology proposal caught him off guard. He said
he would think about it because "there's still some unfinished
business out there among black and white Americans."
</P>
<P>
"I think it has to be dealt with," Clinton told the American
Urban Radio Network. "I think this would be a helpful debate."
</P>
<P>
Slavery was a central theme in the consultations that Clinton
made with activists, scholars and other experts in drafting his
plan for a national dialogue on race. Their advice was that
Clinton first address the lingering wounds of slavery, then try to
resolve the array of racial problems that stem from it.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Clinton "really hasn't
taken a position" on a slavery apology. "But he will look at it in
due course."
</P>
<P>
John Hope Franklin, the historian heading Clinton's advisory
board on race, told reporters over the weekend that Americans need
to expunge "the ideological underpinnings of slavery" that
fostered a belief that black people are "physiologically and
intellectually and ethically inferior." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Calls for World Attention to Desertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations marked the World
Day to Combat Desertification today by calling on the
international community to make further efforts to stop land
degradation and to improve food security in the African Sahel and
in other dryland regions.
</P>
<P>
Land degradation is the leading cause of poverty in the
world's most arid regions, according to a UN press release. Over
250 million people are directly affected by desertification, and
some one billion more are at risk.
</P>
<P>
"In Africa alone, 400 million people live in the dryland
zones," Executive Secretary of the Interim Secretariat for the
United Nations Convention to Combat Desertification Arba Diallo
points out. "They need international support so that they can
adopt sustainable agriculture and land management. It is difficult
for people struggling for their daily bread to make such a major
transition alone."
</P>
<P>
Some 65 percent of Africa's total land area consists of
drylands, with one third of that hyper-arid desert and the rest
arid, semi-arid, and dry sub-humid land. These drylands experience
recurrent droughts -- and with each drought cycle, desertification
increases. As a result, 36 countries in Africa are affected by
drought or by some degree of degradation.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen many positive trends in Africa over the last 20
years," Diallo notes. "Combating land degradation and the poverty
and food insecurity that goes with it is probably the best tool
the world community has to promote political stability, strengthen
civil society, and eliminate conflict and violence in Africa."
</P>
<P>
Africa is not the only continent afflicted by dryland
degradation, the press release warns. Of the world's 1.9 billion
hectares affected by soil degradation, 850 million are in the
densely populated Asia and Pacific region, of which 86 million
hectares are drylands. Parts of Italy, Spain, and other European
countries also suffer, while the continent with the largest area
of damaged drylands is North America.
</P>
<P>
The first conference of the parties to the UN Convention to
Combat Desertification, and other interested countries is
scheduled from September 29 to October 10 in Rome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Urges Negotiated Solutions to Falkland Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 16 (Xinhua) -- The UN Special Committee on
Decolonization Monday asked Argentina and the United Kingdom to
resume negotiations, as soon as possible, towards a peaceful
resolution to the sovereignty dispute over the Falkland Islands.
</P>
<P>
Approving by consensus a draft resolution on the islands,
sponsored by Bolivia, Chile, Papua New Guinea and Venezuela, the
Special Committee reiterated that a peaceful and negotiated
settlement was the way to end the dispute.
</P>
<P>
It also reiterated its firm support for the mission of good
offices of the Secretary-General to assist the parties to comply
with the General Assembly resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Minister for Foreign Affairs of Argentina, Guido Di Tella,
said in cases of contested sovereignty, territorial disputes
should be resolved first, with the applicability for the
self-determination principle being addressed at a later stage.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the new British Government would enter into
dialogue. There was now a new opportunity for two friends to
resolve a colonial anachronism, he said.
</P>
<P>
The position of the United Kingdom is presented in the working
paper on the question of the Falkland Islands.
</P>
<P>
In a statement at the 1996 session of the Assembly, the British
Secretary of State said his government had no doubt about
Britain's sovereignty over the Falkland Islands and the other
British territories in the South Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he hoped the increasing cooperation between
Argentina and the United Kingdom would be further developed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0287 </DOCNO>
