<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Condemns Shootings in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today condemns the "callous murder" by the Irish Republican Army
of two British policemen in the British province of Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Clinton said he condemns the "brutal
act of terrorism in the strongest possible terms," adding, "there
can be no reason, no excuse for these vicious crimes."
</P>
<P>
The policemen were shot as they walked yards from a police
station in Lurgan, south-west of Belfast. They were seriously
wounded and later died.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing patriotic or heroic about these killings. The
overwhelming majority of the people of Ireland, North and South
join me in repudiating violence and murder," Clinton affirmed.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Irish people know that a lasting peace "is
only possible through painful dialogue and negotiation," and
further violence "can only play into the hands of those
responsible for the vicious murders."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he will continue to do all he can to support the
efforts of the Irish people and their political leaders who are
participating in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Condemning the killing, Clinton's Press Secretary Michael
McCurry also called on pro-British Loyalist guerrillas, who have
maintained a shaky truce since October 1994, not to retaliate for
the killings.
</P>
<P>
"The United States government of course will continue to call
on them to honor their own ceasefire and to avoid acts of
retaliation because that sends you into the downward spiral that
is all too familiar to the people of Ireland," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue the contacts that we believe are helpful to
the process, but sooner or later it becomes clear who is willing
to help the process and who is not," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
The IRA ended its 18-month-long ceasefire with a bombing in
London in February 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
