<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Major Computer Makers to Introduce NetPC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 16 (Xinhua) -- At pre-view of the annual PC Expo
trade show here today, 11 big makers of personal computer,
including Compaq, I.B.M., Hewlett-Packard and Dell displayed an
office-friendly model that is called low-cost alternative to
traditional personal computer.
</P>
<P>
Called the NetPC, the new machine has a hard disk drive, memory
and an Intel chip, but it is missing floppy and compact disk
drives to add software and has no expansion slots to add hardware
peripherals.
</P>
<P>
The NetPC is a response to the network computer, or NC, which
has been championed by Sun Microsystem, Oracle Corporation and
I.B.M. The NetPC, which runs Mirosoft's Windows, requires no
investment in new software, unlike the NC. It also has the added
attraction to Sun, Oracle and I.B.M. of being able to use a
variety of microprocessors and operating system software, thereby
challenging the Intel-Microsoft duopoly.
</P>
<P>
Corporate buyers have long complained about the high costs
associated with managing large numbers of personal computers.
expensive staffs are needed to answer questions, untangle hardware
and software conflicts introduced by enterprising employees, and
even do such simple tasks as adding new software.
</P>
<P>
Computer experts maintain that it is not likely that the NetPC
will emerge as much of a threat to the traditional PC. They
estimate that there will be about seven million NetPC's and NC's
sold in the year 2000, compared with more than 100 million
personal computers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workshop on Biodiversity Strategy Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, June 16 (Xinhua) -- A workshop to elaborate "the
national bio-diversity strategy and action plan for Cameroun"
opens today in Limbe, the south west province of Cameroun, local
radio reported here today.
</P>
<P>
"The national bio-diversity strategy and action plan for
Cameroun" falls within the framework of the implementation of
provisions of the Convention on Biological Diversity which
Cameroun ratified in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The convention seeks to protect aquatic and agricultural
resources, the sustainable use as well as the sharing of benefits
from their uses.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day workshop, the participants will examine
findings of consultants and experts on various sectors of
Cameroun's bio-diversity with the view of formulating the most
suitable and realistic strategy for the sustainable use of
biological resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
