<HEADLINE> Croatian President Wins Reelection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 16 (Xinhua) - Croatian president Franjo Tudjman
looks certain to win his reelection bid as preliminary results on
Monday showed him leading his opponents by large margin.
</P>
<P>
According to latest results released by the country's election
commission, Tudjman who represents the ruling Croatian Democratic
Union, won 61.42 percent of the votes, while Social Democratic
candidate Zdravko Tomac got 21.08 percent and Vadimir Gotovac of a
nine-party coalition 17.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that results were based on the vote
counting of 7393 polling stations, just 165 short of the total.
About 2.15 million voters, or 57 percent of eligible voters, cast
their ballots in the 7393 stations.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman was first elected as president in 1990 and re-elected
in 1992 in the first direct presidential election following the
country's independence one year earlier.
</P>
<P>
In his first remarks following the Sunday elections, Tudjman
said that in the next five years of office, he would continue his
policy to establish "a firm and stable democratic political order
and economic stability" in Croatia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
