<DOCNO> XIE19970617.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Immigrant Children More Successful in Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 16 (Xinhua) -- Children of immigrants in the
United States have better grades and lower dropout rates in public
schools than those who were born in the United States, a study
found.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by Michigan State and Princeton
universities and reported in the Los Angeles Times today.
</P>
<P>
Researchers followed 5,000 children in San Diego and Miami
starting in 1991, choosing a sample that represented the immigrant
population in terms of national origin. The children had at least
one foreign-born parent.
</P>
<P>
The grade-point averages (GPAs) of the children were higher
than the district's 133,000 students as a whole. While 29 percent
of all ninth-graders in the district had GPAs higher than 3.0, 44
percent of immigrant children did so. In the 12th grade, 46
percent of all students had at least a "B" average, while 50
percent of immigrant children performed that well.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, only 5.7 percent of the immigrants' children
dropped out, compared with 16.2 percent districtwide.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that immigrant youths placed a high value
on schooling, with more than 90 percent agreeing that a good
education is essential to upward mobility. As high as 63 percent
of Asians and 52 percent of non-Mexican Hispanics said they would
like to earn an advanced degree.
</P>
<P>
Immigrant youths prefer to identify themselves with their
nation of origin are increasing, the study found. In 1992, 43
percent of them chose a hyphenated identity (such as
"Chinese-American") while 32 percent preferred a national origin
label ("Chinese") and 16 percent chose "pan-ethnic" labels
(Asian," "Hispanic"). Only 3 percent chose the plain American
identity.
</P>
<P>
By 1995, the percentage preferring to call themselves merely
Americans in San Diego dropped by half to 1.6 percent by 1995,
while those favoring hyphenated labels dropped by a quarter, to 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
Perception, experiences and expectations of racial
discrimination also increased between 1992 and 1995. By 1995, the
percentage saying they expect to be discriminated against--despite
their educational level--grew from 36 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
